<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> WTO Meeting on Selection of New Leader Ends Without Result </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, May 26 (Xinhua) -- Representatives of the members of
the World Trade Organization (WTO) met here Wednesday in a new
attempt to choose their new leader but failed to reach consensus
on who will lead the organization into the new century.
</P>
<P>
During the three-hour closed-door meeting of the ruling General
Council, WTO members from the Association of South East Asian
Nations (ASEAN) said that, according to the WTO rules, the basic
responsibility of the chairman of the general council is to
facilitate consensus but has no right to eliminate any candidate.
</P>
<P>
The ASEAN countries reaffirmed their support for Thailand's
candidate, Deputy Prime Minister Supachai Panitchpakdi, who is
running for the WTO top job against former New Zealand Premier
Michael Moore.
</P>
<P>
Chairman of the General Council Ali Mchumo, who claimed that
Supachai was out of the race in early May, admitted on Wednesday
that consensus should be built on the two remaining candidates.
But he still insisted that the 134 members of the WTO establish
consensus over his proposal for Moore to be the new
director-general.
</P>
<P>
Former WTO Director-General Renato Ruggiero of Italy retired on
April 30 when his four-year term of office expired, leaving a
power vacuum of the organization since then. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
