<HEADLINE> Abubakar Pledges Military Retreat to Backs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABUJA, May 26 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria's out-going military ruler,
Gen. abdulsalami Abubakar Wednesday promised that the army will
retreat to the backs after the new president assumes power three
days later.
</P>
<P>
He made the pledge while presiding over the valedictory session
of the Provisional Ruling Council in Abuja.
</P>
<P>
The council was the highest policy-making body under the
military's rule, which is to be replaced by the the National
Assembly after Abubakar hands over his power to President-elect
Gen. Olusegun Obasanjo on May 29.
</P>
<P>
The general urged his colleagues in the army, on the occasion
to concentrate on their professional duties.
</P>
<P>
At the meeting, attended also by the out-going 36 state
military administrators and the president-in-waiting, Obasanjo,
Abubakar described the military profession as an honorable one,
which demanded a lot of sacrifice.
</P>
<P>
We must ensure stability by maintaining our professional
integrity, Abubakar said, adding that constitutional role of the
military was mainly to protect the territorial integrity of the
country.
</P>
<P>
The military has ruled Nigeria for almost 30 of its 39 years of
 independence.
</P>
<P>
Abubakar said members of the armed forces must therefore perform
their role with all sense of loyalty and dedication as they go
back to the backs, adding it had been proved that the military
suffered most during military regimes.
</P>
<P>
However, he said that no military adventurer could take over the
 government without the connivance of the civil populace.
</P>
<P>
To stem such a situation, the Nigerian leader called on
Nigerians not to provide the opportunity for anyone or groups to
truncate the democratic process which had cost so much.
</P>
<P>
Highlight of the occasion was the decoration of three state
administrators with their new ranks, among them, Col. Mohammed
Marwa of Lagos state, who was elevated to brigadier general.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
