<HEADLINE> U.S. Says Concerned over Kashmir Fighting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, May 26 (Xinhua) -- the United States said on
Wednesday that it was concerned over the resurgence of fighting
between India and Pakistan in Kashmir following India's bombing on
insurgents in the disputed territory.
</P>
<P>
"The latest fighting underlines the pressing need for India and
Pakistan to resolve their differences," a State Department
official said. "We hope they will be able to do this quickly in
the context of the (February India-Pakistan) summit."
</P>
<P>
India launched two rounds of strikes in norther Kashmir on
Wednesday, using helicopter gunships backed by fighter jets to
strafe ridges inside Indian-controlled territory where it says
hundreds of Pakistan-backed Afghan mercenaries are holed up.
</P>
<P>
It was the first time air power had been used in peacetime
against guerrillas in Kashmir.
</P>
<P>
The official said U.S. embassies in New Delhi and Islamabad had
been instructed to "express concern about the fighting that had
been going on for several days already."
</P>
<P>
Indian Prime Minister Atal Behari Vajpayee signed a pact on
confidence-building measures with Pakistani Prime Minister Nawaz
Sharif on February in the Pakistani city of Lahore on the occasion
of Vajpayee's landmark visit there.
</P>
<P>
But the flare-up fighting refocused world attention on Kashmir
just diplomatic efforts to ease tensions were starting to bear
fruit. 
</P>
</TEXT>
