<HEADLINE> Govt to Make Ugandan Economy Self-Sustainable: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, May 26 (Xinhua) -- President Yoweri Museveni has
clarified Ugandan social and economic recovery programs as
transforming the national economy from a neocolonial type to a
self- sustainable and integrated one.
</P>
<P>
He said this Wednesday when opening a Ministers' and Permanent
Secretaries' retreat in Jinja, 80 kms east of the capital city
Kampala.
</P>
<P>
The president identified for the ministers and permanent
secretaries some of the shortcomings in the implementation of
government programs and in creating conditions for the social
economic recovery of the country, a press release from the
President's Office said.
</P>
<P>
The crucial area of intervention in order to create capacity
for increased incomes for the people is the homestead, he
explained. In this regard, the livestock restocking in northern
Uganda is one way of achieving this goal in that region.
</P>
<P>
The government, he noted, needs to assist farmers in the north
with appropriate agricultural implements such as oxen and ploughs
in order to improve and sustain their agricultural production.
</P>
<P>
He warned against continued frustration of investors and called
upon all relevant organs of government to support programs geared
at export promotion in order to expand the country's export
capacity and increase its foreign exchange earnings.
</P>
<P>
Museveni also talked about the corruption, environmental
degradation, law and order as well as the relationship between the
executive and the legislature.
</P>
<P>
The retreat, whose theme is The Promotion and Strengthening of
Teamwork for Good Governance and Sustainable Development, is
organized by the Ministry of Public Service and will last for four
days. 
</P>
</TEXT>
