<HEADLINE> Addis Administration Distributes land to Residents </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, May 26 (Xinhua) -- The Addis Ababa administration
said Wednesday that it is distributing urban plots of land among
the over 12,000 metropolitans gearing up to construct their
houses.
</P>
<P>
In his report to the13th regular meeting of the administration,
head of the administration Ali Abdo said low income people and
those organized in housing association are receiving land,
according to the Ethiopian News Agency.
</P>
<P>
Ali said the administration has also funded the construction of
2,560 new residential units to alleviate the housing problems in
the capital with a population of 2.3 million.
</P>
<P>
He said work on the construction of 1,500 houses being
undertaken by a private housing organization is also nearing
completion.
</P>
<P>
Local media discovered Saturday that some 1,344 apartment flats
built by the administration in the Kotebe suburbs of Addis at a
cost of over 13 million U.S. dollars have remained vacant for more
than two years. Construction company of the flats was quoted by
the media as saying that " the flats were left idle for such a
long time in a country where housing is a serious problem."
</P>
<P>
"The administration has delayed in relocating residents from
places designated for investment purposes to the Kotebe suburbs,"
Ali said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
