<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Angola's Diamond-Producing Province in Critical </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, May 26 (Xinhua) -- An Angolan general has said the
situation in Lunda-Norte Province, a diamond-producing area in the
northeast, is critical following the beefing up of military
operations by the opposition National Union for th Total
Independence of Angola (UNITA).
</P>
<P>
Sa Miranda, commander of the eastern military command area, was
quoted by a Angola News Agency report Wednesday as saying in Nzaji
in eastern Angola that UNITA forces had cut road links between
Dundo, an interim seat of the provincial government, and other
cities by destroying major bridges, while launching attacks at
major mines.
</P>
<P>
The moves were aimed at paralyzing diamond production in the
province, preventing the free movement of personnel and goods and
occupying some areas of strategic importance, said the general.
</P>
<P>
He added that about 800 UNITA soldiers are concentrating at
Cassai river valley, ready to attack Cambulo City, about 60
kilometers to the southeast of Dundo.
</P>
<P>
Despite the "worrying" situation in the province close to the
Democratic Republic of Congo, the armed forces and national police
have disrupted the strategic arrangement of the UNITA forces
through a series of counter attacks, so that the situation there
is still under the government control, he said.
</P>
<P>
Angola is one of major diamond-producing countries in Africa,
with an output of over two million carats in 1998, most of which
came from the Lunda-norte Province.
</P>
<P>
Since the civil war re-erupted in Angola, both the government
and the UNITA are fighting for the control of the rare resources.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
