<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe's Opposition Disapproves Constitution </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, May 26 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe's opposition party, the
National Constitutional Assembly (NCA), said Wednesday it will
seek public approval next month to institute its own
constitutional reform process outside the government-sanctioned
constitutional commission.
</P>
<P>
NCA Chairman Morgan Tsvangirai told a press conference in
Harare that the assembly, a grouping of civic organizations,
churches and opposition parties, would convene a people's
constitutional convention on June 18 and 19 to seek the way
forward in the formulation of the country's new constitution, the
Zimbabwe News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
He said NCA was opposed to the presidential commission because
the majority of the commissioners were paid-up members of the
ruling Zimbabwe African National Union - Patriotic Front
(ZANU-PF).
</P>
<P>
The commission is expected to consult all Zimbabweans on
provisions of the new constitution which should be drafted by
November.
</P>
<P>
Tsvangirai said NCA was convinced the 398-member government
constitutional commission, sworn into office by President Robert
Mugabe last Friday, did not represent all Zimbabweans.
</P>
<P>
Since the beginning of talks of drafting a new constitution,
the assembly and the government had had differences, and the
government decided to go on with the process without the
assembly's contribution.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwe is using the British-authored Lancaster House
constitution of 1979 which most people feel was out-dated and did
not represent the interests of Zimbabweans. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
