<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia Develops New Navy Missile </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, May 26 (Xinhua) -- Russia announced Wednesday that it
has developed a new anti-ship missile that will "revolutionize the
nature of a naval battle," the Itar-Tass news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The new missile, ZM-54E1, developed by the Novator
Experimental Design Bureau in Yekaterinburg, is 6.2 meters long,
the same as the length of the standard torpedo tubes used by
Western navies, Tass said, quoting Deputy General Designer
Vyacheslav Gorbarenko.
</P>
<P>
"The testing of the new weapon is practically over and the
missile can be delivered to a foreign client within a year after a
corresponding contract is signed," Gorbarenko said.
</P>
<P>
The ZM-54E1 was designed according to the double-stage cruise
scheme, with the first solid-fuel stage ensuring the missile's
blast-off from a universal vertical launcher of a surface craft or
from a submarine torpedo tube with a diameter of 0.533 meters,
Tass said.
</P>
<P>
The second stage sustainer engine goes into action after the
first stage drops off when the missile reaches the prescribed
altitude. This is the time when the missile's wing and tail
assembly unfolds.
</P>
<P>
The altitude of the missiles flight goes down to 10-15 meters
above the sea surface and the missile heads towards the target in
accordance with the target designations, fed before the start into
the memory of its on-board guidance system.
</P>
<P>
The targeting on the cruise sector of the missile is achieved
by an inertia navigation system and the end sector of the
missile's flight with the homing head active proceeds only five
meters above the water surface.
</P>
<P>
The missile, with a launch weight of 1,570 kilograms, has a
range of 300 kilometers and a powerful 450-kilogram warhead, which
can blow up very large surface craft, Tass said.
</P>
<P>
"Delivery of new Russian missiles will be effected together
with the entire missile set, which includes ZM-54E1 missiles, fire-
control system, launcher, ground servicing system, and trainer,"
Gorbarenko said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
