<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwean Government Urged to Reduce Poverty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, May 26 (Xinhua) -- The Zimbabwean government must
pursue policies designed to achieve price stability and rapid
economic growth to reduce poverty, the Poverty Reduction Forum
(PRF) has said.
</P>
<P>
In its Human Development Report released here Wednesday, the
forum said weak economic growth, rising unemployment and a skewed
pattern of income and wealth distribution had resulted in the
increase in poverty, the Zimbabwe News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The report said economic growth had drastically slowed down
after the introduction of the Economic Structural Adjustment
Program in 1990.
</P>
<P>
The program was aimed to establish an environment conducive to
sustainable economic growth and development.
</P>
<P>
"Most macro-economic targets were missed, inflation
accelerated, unemployment and poverty increased," the report said.
</P>
<P>
It noted that low job creation in the formal sector had
resulted in school leavers being pushed into the informal sector
which had low technology and short life span.
</P>
<P>
It was estimated that since 1990 the formal sector had created
less than 25,000 new jobs which could not satisfy the 300,000
school leavers who searched for jobs annually.
</P>
<P>
The report recommended good governance, transparency and
accountability to eliminate corruption and reallocate public
spending to activities beneficial to the poor. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
