<HEADLINE> Zambian Financial Institutions Urged to Assist </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, May 26 (Xinhua) -- The Zambian government has called on
 financial institutions in the country to assist small scale
business enterprises to have access to credit and other financial
services in order to promote economic development.
</P>
<P>
James Mtonga, permanent secretary in the Ministry of Finance
and Economic Development, said here Wednesday that the small scale
sector had great potential to contribute significantly toward
sustainable growth and poverty reduction in Zambia.
</P>
<P>
Mtonga, however, noted that the amount of capital available in
developing countries was not adequate to sustain development. He
welcomed the efforts by the Zambia Union of Savings and Credit
Association Trust (ZUSCT) to revive the credit unions network in
the country.
</P>
<P>
Officially opening a ZUSCT workshop here, Mtonga said the
government was committed to maintaining a sound and stable
financial sector in order to achieve a higher rate of growth
through increased savings and investment.
</P>
<P>
The government would also ensure that a sound banking system
that promotes development and growth of financial intermediation
was maintained in addition to protecting depositors, he said.
</P>
<P>
He further noted that without a stable financial system there
would be a breakdown in the nation's payment system which was
largely administered by banks and credit unions.
</P>
<P>
He said the number of banks in Zambia had increased from 12 to
over 20 as a result of liberalization and sound economic policies
the government had put in place since 1991.
</P>
<P>
Zambia would need efficient financial intermediation in order
to foster high export-led growth and create employment
opportunities in the private sector, he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
