<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Bank Lends 250 Million Dollars to China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, May 26 (Xinhua) -- The World Bank approved on
Wednesday a total of 250 million U.S. dollars in loans and credits
to help China increase the incomes of poor farmers and
agricultural production.
</P>
<P>
The bank's executive board approved a 80-million-dollar loan
and a 20-million-dollar credit for the Guanzhong Irrigation
Improvement Project and a 100-million-dollar loan and a
50-million-dollar credit for the Second Loess Plateau Watershed
Rehabilitation Project.
</P>
<P>
The Guanzhong Irrigation Improvement Project aims to increase
grain production in the nine Irrigation District areas, increase
the incomes of farmers, and strengthen irrigation management in
the Guanzhong Plain in the Wei River Valley of Shanxi Province,
the bank said.
</P>
<P>
The objective of the Second Loess Plateau Watershed
Rehabilitation Project is to help achieve sustainable development
by increasing agricultural production and incomes, and improving
ecological conditions in tributary watersheds of the Yellow River.
</P>
<P>
Under the project, moderately sloped land will be converted to
high-yielding terraced cropland, and the steeper slopes will be
planted to a range of trees, shrubs and grasses. Sediment control
structures will reduce erosion from the gullies and create
valuable farmland.
</P>
<P>
The primary beneficiaries of the project are poor people living
in remote villages in the area. Of the 37 counties in the project,
19 are classified by the government as amongst the poorest in
China.
</P>
<P>
The two loans would be at the bank's interest rate for
LIBOR-based U.S. dollar single-currency loans, with a maturity of
20 years, including a five-year grace period. The two credits,
provided by the International Development Association (IDA), the
bank's concessionary lending arm, would be on standard IDA terms
with 35 years' maturity. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990527.0032 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IDB Supports Education Reform in Trinidad and Tobago </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, May 26 (Xinhua) -- The Inter-American Development
Bank (IDB) announced on Wednesday the approval of a loan amounting
to 105 million U.S. dollars to Trinidad and Tobago to help reform
and expand secondary education.
</P>
<P>
The resources will enable the Ministry of Education to
undertake a program designed to create a base of skills that are
essential to sustaining the country's economic growth in the next
century by enhancing the population's technical and managerial
capacity, the Washington-based bank said.
</P>
<P>
Among the investments will be the introduction of a more modern
curriculum and new instructional resources, establishment of a
magnet school program to promote excellence and innovation,
professional development of teachers and other staff, the
rehabilitation and upgrading of school infrastructure, and
institutional strengthening of the Ministry of Education, the bank
said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
A goal a of the project is to provide greater access, quality
and coverage of the secondary education system for low-income
groups, and advance toward achieving universal secondary coverage
from its current rate of 69 percent.
</P>
<P>
Components of the program include the installation of computer
laboratories in all 100 existing secondary schools and the
construction of 20 new schools.
</P>
<P>
The total cost of the program is 150 million dollars. The IDB
loan is for a 25-year term, with a seven-year grace period, at the
variable interest rate, now 6.98 percent. Local counterpart funds
total 45 million dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
