<DOCNO> XIE19990527.0033 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Senate Rejects Plan for More Military Base Closings </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, May 26 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. Senate Wednesday
rejected the Bill Clinton administration's request to close more
military bases as a cost-saving measure.
</P>
<P>
The 60-to-40 Senate vote rejected a move by Republican Senator
John McCain and Democratic Senator Carl Levin to authorize a new
round of base closings in 2001.
</P>
<P>
This was the third year in a row Congress has blocked the plan.
</P>
<P>
The administration has argued that many of the bases are relics
of the Cold War, and shutting them down could free up funds that
could be used to modernize weapons and to meet other pressing
Pentagon needs.
</P>
<P>
Defense Secretary William Cohen contends that closing
antiquated bases -- many of them Cold War relics -- could save the
Pentagon nearly four billion U.S. dollars a year that would be
better spent on aircraft carriers, jet fighters and other crucial
hardware.
</P>
<P>
However, Congress has always been reluctant to close bases.
</P>
<P>
The government's proposal for two new rounds of base closings
-- one in 2001 and another in 2005 -- was rejected earlier this
month by the Armed Services panel.
</P>
<P>
The debate occurred as the Senate worked on a
288.8-billion-U.S.-dollar defense spending bill for the fiscal
year that begins next October 1. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990527.0034 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Security Council Voices "Deep Concern" at Humanitarian  Situation in Angola </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, May 26 (Xinhua) -- The U.N. Security Council
Wednesday voiced "deep concern" at the humanitarian situation in
Angola, saying that it is the responsibility of the Angolan
Government and the rebel National Union for Total Independence of
Angola (UNITA) to cooperate with the United Nations in rendering
humanitarian assistance to all the people in need.
</P>
<P>
In a statement read to the press here, the president of the
15-nation body, Denis Dangue Rewaka of Gabon, said, "Members of
the Council reiterated their deep concern at the continuing
deterioration of the humanitarian situation in Angola and at the
ever increasing number of internally displaced persons that has
now reached the number of 1.6 million."
</P>
<P>
"They expressed particular concern over the dramatic reduction
of the operational space available to humanitarian agencies
throughout Angola, as a consequence of which large parts of the
territory of Angola remain unaccessible for the humanitarian
community and large parts of the population in need are not
reached," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
"Members of the Council emphasized once again the
responsibility of the Government of Angola and UNITA to cooperate
with U.N. and other organizations in their humanitarian assistance
to all those in need and to guarantee unconditionally the security
and freedom of movement of humanitarian personnel," the statement
said.
</P>
<P>
"In this regard, members of the Council reaffirmed
international convention on the treatment of civilians in times of
war and underlined the importance of the principles of neutrality
and impartiality in th delivery of humanitarian assistance
throughout the territory," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
"Members of the Council expressed outrage at recent attacks by
UNITA on civilian population, humanitarian relief workers and
civilians aircraft, provoking a number of deaths and injuries and
the destruction of property and jeopardizing humanitarian
deliveries," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Security Council "reiterate their call for the
immediate release of the 3 crew members of the downed Antonov-26
by UNITA," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
The statement came after the Security Council met in a
closed-door session to be briefed by the U.N. Secretariat on the
latest humanitarian situation in the southwest African country.
</P>
<P>
"Members of the Council affirmed that the obligation to
facilitate humanitarian assistance applies equally to all parties
to a conflict and underlined that it is vital for the humanitarian
community to be allowed access for assessment missions and to
develop mechanisms for the delivery of humanitarian assistance to
all populations in need throughout the territory," the statement
said.
</P>
<P>
The Security Council on Wednesday last week strongly condemned
a "criminal act" by UNITA in shooting down a Russian Antonov-26
commercial aircraft on May 12 and "taking hostage" its Russian
crew.
</P>
<P>
Reports from northern Angola said the aircraft, brought down by
a missile, carried three Russian crew and two Angolans.
</P>
<P>
A 1994 peace accord between the Angolan Government and UNITA,
which the United Nations had been helping to implement, fell apart
during the past year and full-scale civil war resumed in many
parts of the country.
</P>
<P>
The Security Council is still waiting for the outcomes of the
investigations into the downing of two U.N.-chartered cargo planes
in Angola on December 26, 1998 and on January 2, 1999, in which 23
people were killed.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
