<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Greece Seeks Pause in NATO Bombing Against Yugoslavia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, May 26 (Xinhua) -- Greek Foreign Minister George
Papandreou Wednesday called for a pause in NATO bombing of
Yugoslavia to encourage Yugoslavia to respond positively to tough
demands for settlement of the Kosovo conflict.
</P>
<P>
After a meeting with U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright, Papandreou reaffirmed the Greek proposal that there
should be a pause in NATO's bombing to give some stimulus to the
diplomatic efforts.
</P>
<P>
"We feel that the proposal, this idea of the bombing pause, can
be one which might be necessary, might be able to be used at some
point which will further spur on diplomatic efforts and
particularly help a U.N. resolution in the Security Council," he
said.
</P>
<P>
"Greece, being in the region and feeling the direct effects of
what's going in the region, has put great emphasis in working on
the diplomatic front and being helpful," Papandreou said.
</P>
<P>
However, speaking at a joint press conference with Albright,
Papandreou also said, "I want to be very clear on this, is that
obviously the five positions stand and they must be met with and
agreed upon."
</P>
<P>
Albright appeared to rule the idea of a pause out, reiterating
that the bombing would be halted only if Yugoslavia accepted
NATO's demands.
</P>
<P>
She also praised Greece as playing an important role in Kosovo,
even though it was not participating in the attacks on Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
Of the 19 NATO nations, Greece probably is the most skeptical
that all-out bombing will bring Belgrade to bow before NATO.
</P>
</TEXT>
