<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Diplomat Refutes U.S. Espionage Allegation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, May 26 (Xinhua) -- A Senior Chinese Diplomat
refuted here Wednesday the U.S. allegation that China has "stolen"
nuclear secrets from the United States.
</P>
<P>
"As Chinese leaders and spokesman of the Chinese government
have repeatedly said, China has never stolen any nuclear secrets
from the United States, " said Liu Xiaoming, Minister of the
Chinese Embassy in the United States, in a CNN interview.
</P>
<P>
Liu said the Cox Report is "full of unproven allegations and
vague languages such as maybe and possibly, there is no solid
evidence to support those allegations".
</P>
<P>
A U.S. House Committee headed by Republican Representative
Christopher Cox issued an 872-page report Tuesday, alleging that
China got secret information on seven nuclear warheads and the
neutron bomb through "espionage" at U.S. nuclear weapons
laboratories.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the Cox report, Liu said some politicians here try
to "play politics and make China as victim of their partisan
politics".
</P>
<P>
Liu said the Cox report tries to regard China as a "threat" to
the United States, but China will not threaten the United States.
</P>
<P>
"China is the least country among the major nuclear powers
which can pose a threat to the United States as China is the only
country which has undertaken the obligation not to use nuclear
weapons first," Liu said.
</P>
<P>
Liu said he was not concerned at all over the investigations
being conducted by several U.S. Congress committees since China
has done nothing wrong, what he was concerned about is the
U.S.-China relations.
</P>
<P>
"If you have not done anything wrong, you do not fear that a
ghost will knock at your door at midnight," Liu said, citing an
old Chinese saying.
</P>
<P>
"I am concerned that some people will use the report to stir up
anti-China sentiment to derail the relationship and undo the
progress made by our two countries in the past years," he said.
</P>
<P>
"I am also concerned that a hostile atmosphere might be
created for the Chinese Americans working here and for the
Chinese students and scholars studying here. They have done a
great deal to contribute to the progress of American society,"
he added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
