<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. African Soldiers Allowed to Joint Trade Unions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, May 26 (Xinhua) -- Members of the South African
National Defense Force (SANDF) will from Wednesday be legally
allowed to join labor unions following a Constitutional Court
ruling.
</P>
<P>
The Constitutional Court Wednesday confirmed a Pretoria High
Court judgment last year that it was unconstitutional to prohibit
members of the SANDF to join trade unions.
</P>
<P>
The judgment ended an almost five-year battle by the South
African National Defense Union (SANDU) to have their union
declared legal.
</P>
<P>
The union was established in 1994 but was illegal in terms of
the Defense Act which prohibited members from joining trade unions
or participating in protest action.
</P>
<P>
Pretoria High Court judge WJ Hartzenbeg ruled last November
that this section of the Defense Act, prohibiting members from
joining trade unions was unconstitutional.
</P>
<P>
Constitutional Court judge Kate O'Regan delivered the judgment
on behalf of the Constitutional Court judges, saying the court
decided that prohibiting participation in acts of public protests
violated the right to freedom of expression of defense force
members.
</P>
<P>
This amounted to a grave infringement on the fundamental rights
of soldiers.
</P>
<P>
The court placed a three-month delay on the order to allow the
SANDF to get its house in order.
</P>
<P>
But, it added a provision that if the delayed order caused any
party substantial prejudice, such party may approach the court
again.
</P>
<P>
The ruling, however, does not change the fact that uniformed
members would not be allowed to strike. The court said in its
judgment the union accepted that strike action was inappropriate
in the military context but this should not prevent members from
joining trade unions.
</P>
<P>
SANDU national secretary Cor van Niekerk said Wednesday's
Constitutional Court ruling could have serious repercussions for
the South African National Defense Force's transformation and
rationalization policies.
</P>
<P>
He said the union warned the SANDF some time ago to allow the
union to participate in decisions which could affect soldiers.
</P>
<P>
"We warned them we expected the union to be legalized. These
unilateral decisions taken by the SANDF will now be challenged."
</P>
<P>
Wednesday's decision made South Africa only one of nine
countries in the world to declare a defense force union legal.
</P>
<P>
Van Niekerk said South Africa was also the only country on the
African continent to afford its soldiers these rights.
</P>
<P>
The union currently represents between 15,000 and 17,000
members.
</P>
<P>
Van Niekerk said these members joined while it was still
illegal for them to join.
</P>
<P>
"We expect that we could have between 40,000 and 50,000 members
within three months. The potential is 100,000 members," he said.
</P>
<P>
SANDF spokesman Colonel John Rolt said the defense force took
note of the judgment and was studying it. He could therefore not
comment further, SAPA said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
