<HEADLINE> U.N. Special Envoy to Visit Colombia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, May 26 (Xinhua) -- Olara Otunnu, U.N. special
envoy for children and armed conflict, is expected to pay a visit
to Colombia next week "to assess first-hand the conditions of
children affected by the protracted civil war" in the Latin
American country, U.N. officials said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
He is also expected to "explore concrete ways to more
effectively protect affected children, and to promote the
inclusion of the welfare of children on the peace agenda for
Colombia," the officials said.
</P>
<P>
The special envoy will visit Bogota, Medellin and Apartado, and
he will hold talks with the president, vice president, the high
commissioner for peace and the ministers of external affairs,
defense and interior.
</P>
<P>
During his visit, he will meet with leaders of the two main
guerrilla movements, the Revolutionary Armed Forces of Colombia
(FARC) and the National Liberation Army (ELN).
</P>
<P>
Otunnu will visit war-dispatched populations as well as "peace
communities" in the Uruba region. Throughout his visit, he will
hold discussions with representatives of international and local
NGOs. church groups and other civil society organizations.
</P>
<P>
The special envoy will devote particular attention to issues of
child recruitment and participation in the armed conflict, the
targetting of civilian populations by armed groups and forces, the
displacement of civilian populations, the need to provide basic
educational and medical facilities for affected children, and the
importance of placing children's needs and protection on the peace
agenda for Colombia.
</P>
<P>
It will be the special representative's first mission to Latin
America. Otunnu, who serves as international advocate for children
affected by armed conflict by promoting their rights, protection
and welfare, has previously undertaken missions to Albania,
Burundi, Kosovo in Yugoslavia, Liberia, Macedonia, Mozambique,
Rwanda, Sierra Leone, Sri Lanka and Sudan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
