<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Profile: Nepal's New Prime Minister K.P. Bhattarai </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, May 27 (Xinhua) -- Krishna Prasad Bhattarai Thursday
fulfilled his long-cherished dream of returning to the premiership
of Nepal at last, but only eight years later.
</P>
<P>
On April 19, 1990, he was named by King Birendra to head an
interim government to draft a new constitution and hold general
elections.
</P>
<P>
The constitution provides for a constitutional monarchy in
Nepal. In the May 1991 general elections, the Nepali Congress, of
which Bhattarai was acting president, secured a majority of seats
but Bhattarai lost at the height of his popularity and stepped
down that month.
</P>
<P>
He lost again in the by-election to the House of
Representatives in February 1994.
</P>
<P>
However, he won by a wide margin in the elections held on May
17. "God goaded the voters to catch me while I'm still active," he
said when asked who he would like to thank for the victory. Months
before the elections, he had been offered the premiership by party
President and Prime Minister Girija Prasad Koirala.
</P>
<P>
Bhattarai was born on December 22, 1924, in Benaras, India. He
was one of the commanders during the Nepalese revolution against
the 104-year-old autocratic Rana regime in November 1950.
</P>
<P>
He was unanimously elected speaker of the first elected
parliament in Nepal in 1959-60. He was imprisoned in December 1960
when King Mahendra, King Birendra's father, staged a royal coup
and dissolved the parliament.
</P>
<P>
Bhattarai was incarcerated for about 14 years during the king's
"one-man rule" which lasted for 30 years until a pro-democracy
movement in early 1990, in which Bhattarai was a chief leader,
reinstated the multi-party parliamentary system in the kingdom.
</P>
<P>
Bhattarai is a bachelor. "They took me to jail when I was
young, and (I) was released when I became old -- perhaps too old
for young and energetic women," he once teased.
</P>
<P>
Reading sacred verses from Hindu scripture Geeta has been a
part of Bhattarai's routine for years. A two-mile walk and yoga
are his two other morning occupations.
</P>
<P>
To Bhattarai, accepting the post of prime minister is to take a
divine order to embark on a mission. But to illiterate Nepalese,
this is incomprehensible.
</P>
<P>
"That is why I want to raise the literacy rate to 90 percent
from the present level of 40 percent," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990527.0045 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Barak: Shas Should be Included in Coalition </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, May 27 (Xinhua)-- Israel's religious party Shas
should be asked to join and play its role in the incoming
coalition government, Prime Minister-elect Ehud Barak said
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a gathering in Israel's northern town of Qir
Shemona, Barak said the Shas is an important political party and
there is no reason why it should not be allowed to join the
coalition government, according to Israel Radio.
</P>
<P>
Barak said Shas has contributed a lot to the Israeli society
and the door is open for it to join the coalition.
</P>
<P>
But One Israel's sister party Meretz still refuses to sit
in the coalition government together with Shas.
</P>
<P>
Meretz made this stand clear Thursday afternoon at Herzliya
where One Israel's negotiating team started its second round of
coalition talks with the political parties which won Knesset
(parliament) seats.
</P>
<P>
Meretz will not sit in the government with the right-wing
party such as Shas whose leader was sentenced to a four-year
imprisonment for fraud and taking bribery, Meretz was reportedly
told One Israel at the talks.
</P>
<P>
Barak expressed his hope that Meretz will change its attitude
toward Shas and work with it in the coalition.
</P>
<P>
Shas won 17 Knesset seats in the May 17 elections, becoming the
third largest party in the Knesset just behind One Israel and
Likud. Meretz got 10 seats
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Barak reiterated his pledge to pull out Israel
Defense Force (IDF) soldiers from the security zone in south
Lebanon within one year.
</P>
<P>
He said this will not affect the IDF's morale, but the biggest
issue for his government is to find out effective ways to
guarantee Israel's northern security.
</P>
<P>
Israel set up the security zone in 1985 in south Lebanon in a
self-proclaimed purpose of protecting is northern security.
</P>
<P>
Local military groups such as Hezbollah have been waging
military resistance against the IDF since then, causing a
considerable amount of casualties among the IDF officers and
soldiers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
