<HEADLINE> China to Speed up Nuclear Power Self-reliance Process </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 27 (Xinhua) -- A senior official with China's
Commission of Science, Technology and Industry for National
Defense said today that "China hopes that nuclear power technology
transfers from abroad will help speed up the country's nuclear
power self-reliance process."
</P>
<P>
Xu Yumin, director of the Second Systems Engineering Bureau of
the commission, made the remark here today at a seminar on Sino-
France nuclear power technology transfers.
</P>
<P>
Jointly sponsored by three French companies, EDF, FRAMATOME and
ALSTOM, the seminar is being attended by nearly 200 nuclear power
specialists, scholars, and related government officials from China
and France.
</P>
<P>
The participants discussed the development of nuclear power
technology in China since its opening and reform, especially the
process of self-reliance for China's nuclear power industry.
</P>
<P>
Jean-Daniel Levi, executive vice president of FRAMATOME,
recalled the 20-year sincere cooperation in the field of nuclear
power industry between China and France, giving high credit to the
fruitful accomplishments achieved by China during the process of
becoming self-reliant in the nuclear power industry, referring to
French nuclear power technology and know-how.
</P>
<P>
The French government also pays great attention to Sino-
France cooperation. French ambassador to China, Pierre Morel, also
attended the seminar, and said the French government is very happy
to see these three French companies participating in the process
of and making contributions to self-reliance for China's nuclear
power industry.
</P>
<P>
The French and Chinese specialists, and officials
participating in the seminar held talks on nuclear power project
design and management, device manufacturing, engineering
construction, and testing and operations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
