<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tianjin Protecting Legal Rights and Interests of Overseas Investors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIANJIN, May 27 (Xinhua) -- To safeguard the legal rights and
interests of overseas-funded enterprises in Tianjin in north China
is the responsibility of the municipal government and is essential
for ensuring that the businesses profit locally.
</P>
<P>
Li Shenglin, mayor of Tianjin, made these remarks at a
symposium on the local investment environment attended by
officials of more than 20 local departments and representatives of
20 large local overseas-funded enterprises.
</P>
<P>
Problems that overseas investors want to resolve focus on
their lack of access to the policy process of local government,
non-reasonable fees charged on some monopolized sectors, and the
year 2000 computer problem, popularly known as the millennium bug
or Y2K.
</P>
<P>
Li Shenglin announced a deadline for resolving some of these
problems.
</P>
<P>
Priority is being given to standardizing fee charges on
enterprises, and reducing fees to the lowest possible level as an
effort toward reducing non-production costs for local overseas-
funded enterprises.
</P>
<P>
Tianjin now has more than 12,000 overseas-funded enterprises
involving 24.1 billion U.S. dollars of overseas investment. Some 4,
000 overseas-funded local enterprises are doing well, contributing
more than 40 percent of the local industrial output value and more
than 70 percent of local exports annually.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
