<DOCNO> XIE19990527.0050 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai Candidate Stays in the WTO Race: Chuan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, May 27 (Xinhua) -- Thai Commerce Minister Supachai
Panitchpakdi will not withdraw from the deadlocked race for the
directorship of the World Trade Organization (WTO), Thai Prime
Minister Chuan Leekpai said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Chuan made the remarks after another meeting of the WTO's
decision-making general council on Wednesday in Geneva failed once
again to solve the impasse between the Thai candidate and his New
Zealand rival, Mike Moore.
</P>
<P>
Chuan said that if the current selection process goes ahead,
Supachai, who is also the government's deputy prime minister, will
stay in.
</P>
<P>
However, he admitted that if the process is taken back to the
very beginning, Supachai may withdraw.
</P>
<P>
The struggle for the leadership of the 134-member world trade
body has lasted for several months. No consensus can be formed
around either Supachai or Moore.
</P>
<P>
Thailand has blamed the United States for blocking its
candidate, who had been leading in earlier rounds of the selection
process. 
</P>
</TEXT>
