<HEADLINE> Giraffes Survive Long Journey to Reach Northwest China Zoo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LANZHOU, May 27 (Xinhua) -- Two young giraffes arrived here
today at the city zoo of this capital of northwest China's Gansu
Province after a long and dangerous journey that lasted three days
and nights.
</P>
<P>
The giraffes, the first for the 40-year-old zoo, are both
around two-and-a-half-years old and over three meters tall, and
they came here from Qinhuangdao, a port city in the northern
province of Hebei some 2,100 kilometers from Lanzhou.
</P>
<P>
"We have long expected to have giraffes in our zoo, but we
failed to do so because of transportation difficulties," said a
manager at the Lanzhou zoo, which also has rare animals including
the giant panda and golden monkeys.
</P>
<P>
A zoo vet explained that because the giraffe is very tall and
has very high blood pressure, it's quite easy for the animal to
die of a broken neck or burst blood vessels during long-distance
transportation. The height of an adult giraffe can reach six
meters.
</P>
<P>
"This time, we took special precautions with the transportation
vehicles, and several of our staff escorting the giraffes got only
two hours of sleep during the journey," said the zoo manager.
</P>
<P>
The Lanzhou zoo has spent more than 600,000 yuan (about 75,000
U.S. dollars) building a special residence for the giraffes, which
are expected to be able to meet visitors before International
Children's Day on June 1.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990527.0058 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-27 </DATE_TIME>
