<HEADLINE> Interim Chittagong Hill Tracts Council Installed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, May 27 (Xinhua) -- A 22-member interim Chittagong Hill
Tracts Regional Council(CHTRC) was formally set up in Bangladesh's
southeastern hill district of Rangamati Thursday in realization of
the 1997 CTH Peace Agreement, the national news agency BSS
reported.
</P>
<P>
The CHT (Chittagong Hill Tracts) Peace Agreement was signed in
December 1997 between the government and the tribal organization,
ending a more-then-two-decade-long insurgency in the CHT.
</P>
<P>
"This is an auspicious journey and the moment historic for the
people of the hill districts as well as the nation," Jyotirrindra
Bodhipriya Larma, who took over as chairman of the CHTRC on May
12.
</P>
<P>
The council's establishment ended an eight-month-long deadlock
in implementing a major provision of the peace accord.
</P>
<P>
Larma reiterated his appeal to the government for "quick and
proper" implementation of the pact including withdrawal of army
camps in the 11,655 square kilometer rugged region in line with
the accord, the report said.
</P>
<P>
He urged his former rival, the security forces, to forget the
past and move together for the development of the region.
</P>
<P>
"The tribal people may still have repulsion toward you and you
too may have similar feeling, but let us leave the past behind,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
Thousands of guests including government leaders, diplomats,
tribal and Bengali representatives and ex-rebels witnessed the
event.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
