<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Divers Gear Up for FINA Diving Grand Prix Meeting in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WENZHOU, May 28 (Xinhua) -- All the 11 participating teams for
the FINA Diving Grand Prix meeting, the eighth leg of the 14-leg
1999 FINA Diving Grand Prix series, have arrived here for the
opening round competition in the southeastern Chinese city of
Wenzhou on Friday.
</P>
<P>
The participating list has been shortened, from the originally-
registered 15 teams to the current 11. Among the missing sides
are Russia and the United States, due to reasons ranging from lack
of financial support and conflicting schedule. The participants
are from Australia, Canada, Germany, Indonesia, Japan, South Korea,
Ukraine, Hong Kong and hosts China.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong, which is now a special administrative region of
China, is represented at the event by a single diver.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese Swimming Association (CSA) has entered two teams,
fielding such world-class divers as former Olympic and world
champion as well as World Cup winners Fu Mingxia, Xiong Ni and Sun
Shuwei.
</P>
<P>
But the veteran Chinese face an increasingly tough challenge
from such teenager stars as Sang Xue, Liang Xiaoqiao and Guo
Jingjing.
</P>
<P>
For Chinese, the Wenzhou event is one of the five meetings
through which they could obtain qualifying points for their
individual participation at the 2000 Olympic Games in Sydney.
Other qualifying events include two national events, two
international competitions and the 2000 FINA Diving World Cup in
Sydney.
</P>
<P>
There are six events in the Grand Prix meeting starting here on
Friday: one-meter and three-meter springboard events and 10-meter
platform events for men and women.
</P>
<P>
The Wenzhou event closes on Sunday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
