<HEADLINE> Mallon Urges Setting up N.Irish Executive </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, May 27 (Xinhua) -- Northern Ireland's Deputy First
Minister Seamus Mallon called for both sides in the standoff to
end the deadlock and establish the local executive as early as
possible.
</P>
<P>
"We do not have any more time to waste," said Mallon, also
deputy leader of the Social Democratic and Labor Party in Belfast.
</P>
<P>
Mallon called on the Ulster Unionists and Sinn Fein to move
away from their absolutist positions to end the deadlock over
decommissioning.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Tony Blair has set a deadline of June 30 for a
settlement to the deadlock over the decommissioning of
paramilitary weapons -- the issue which has delayed the setting up
of the ruling body in Belfast.
</P>
<P>
Ulster Unionist Party has said the Irish Republican Army or IRA
must begin a credible and verifiable weapons handover before its
political wing Sinn Fein can take its two seats in the 10 member
executive.
</P>
<P>
But Sinn Fein insists decommissioning is not a condition under
the Good Friday Agreement.
</P>
<P>
Failure to set up the cabinet on time "would be a victory for
those who thrive on division, death and destruction," Mallon said.
</P>
</TEXT>
