<HEADLINE> U.S. Repeats Concern over Kashmir Violence </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, May 27 (Xinhua) -- The United States repeated its
concern on Thursday over the resurgent fighting in Kashmir and
called upon India and Pakistan to halt conflict.
</P>
<P>
"We are concerned about the rising escalation of violence in
Kashmir," said Michael Hammer, a spokesman for the National
Security Council. "We have appealed to the governments in both
India and Pakistan to abide by the terms of the Lahore accords."
</P>
<P>
India and Pakistan agreed in February at a summit in the
Pakistani city of Lahore to solve dispute over Kashmir peacefully.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. ambassador to India Richard Celeste carried the
Clinton administration's appeal for restraint to India's defense
minister and U.S. diplomats in Islamabad met with Pakistani
officials in a separate visit, Hammer said.
</P>
<P>
So far, U.S. officials have yet to send a senior State
Department envoy to either capital.
</P>
<P>
Strobe Talbott, the U.S. Deputy Secretary of State who
spearheaded efforts to bring Indian and Pakistani officials
together in Lahore, is unavailable.  
</P>
