<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Philippine Senate Ratifies VFA Amid Protest </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, May 27 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine Senate ratified
Thursday evening the Philippines-U.S. Visiting Forces Agreement
(VFA) by a vote of 18 for and 5 against.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, thousands of protesters rallied in the rain outside
the senate building against the ratification of the controversial
pact.
</P>
<P>
A TV survey conducted Thursday showed that nearly 60 percent of
the Filipinos are against the VFA.
</P>
<P>
Under the Philippine Constitution, the VFA needs at least 16
votes or two-thirds of the 23-member senate to be ratified.
</P>
<P>
The VFA, which was signed by Philippine and U.S. officials last
year, would allow the United States to resume major ship visits
and large-scale joint war exercises in the Philippines which were
suspended in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Supporters say the VFA will help protect regional peace and
stability and strengthen the Philippine Armed Forces as well as
the political, economic and security linkages with the United
States.
</P>
<P>
But critics say the pact would limit the Philippine
government's right to prosecute American soldiers who commit
crimes in the country, promote prostitution and drag the
Philippines into conflicts with enemies of the United States.
</P>
<P>
During the debates, Senator Teofisto Guingona said the VFA will
place the Philippines on unequal footing with the United States
because "Filipino soldiers who will be going to the U.S. are not
going to enjoy the same protection as U.S. personnel enjoyed in
the Philippines."
</P>
<P>
Senator Aquilino Pimentel said he rejected the VFA because it
is silent on the constitutional ban on the entry of nuclear
weapons into the Philippines by visiting U.S. forces.
</P>
<P>
Loren Legarda, the youngest senator, said she voted against it
because the Philippine Constitution states that there should be no
foreign troops based in the Philippines.
</P>
<P>
Furthermore, there is no provision in the pact for the
protection of the environment, Legarda said.
</P>
<P>
"We do not want a repeat of the experience in Clark and Subic
where the U.S. military forces left toxic wastes and refused to
clean them," she said.
</P>
<P>
In recent weeks, protesters have held almost daily
demonstrations outside the Philippine Senate and the U.S. Embassy.
</P>
<P>
Anti-VFA groups held a vigil in front of the senate from
Wednesday night. A group of running priests with a giant streamer
against the VFA held a brief demonstration in front of the U.S.
Embassy early Thursday morning and ran later to the senate
building to join other protesters.
</P>
<P>
Also on Thursday morning, a group of women installed an altar
with the image of Virgin Mary and held a mass in front of the U.S.
Embassy after setting American flags on fire.
</P>
<P>
Several hundred soldiers and policemen were deployed in front
of the Senate building Thursday to guard against the angry
protesters.
</P>
<P>
The Philippines' two largest rebel groups, National Democratic
Front (NDF) and Moro Islamic Liberation Front (MILF), have
threatened to terminate peace talks with the government if the VFA
is ratified, saying the accord would negate their future demands
for reforms.
</P>
<P>
The Philippines signed a Mutual Defense Treaty with Washington
in 1951. Officials in both countries say joint exercises are
needed to ensure good cooperation and communication between the
two militaries.
</P>
<P>
A separate agreement shielding U.S. military personnel from
prosecution for crimes committed in the Philippines was canceled
by Manila in December 1996, prompting the United States to halt
major military exercises with the country.
</P>
<P>
Military ties with the United States, which ruled the
Philippines for nearly half a century, have remained a sensitive
issue since the Philippine Senate forced the closure of the last
U.S. base in 1992. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
