<HEADLINE> Feeble Shock Hits Northern Philippines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, May 27 (Xinhua) -- An earthquake measuring 4.9 on the
Richter scale shook the northern Philippines Thursday afternoon,
but no damage was expected, the Philippine Institute of
Volcanology and Seismology said.
</P>
<P>
In a preliminary report issued here, the institute said the
epicenter was in Iba, 59 kilometers north of Zambles.
</P>
<P>
The earthquake occurred at 14:18 (06:18 GMT) and aftershocks
were expected, the institute said.
</P>
<P>
The possible source of the feeble shock is from the Manila
trench, it said.
</P>
<P>
The quake was felt in Manila and buildings in the area swung
for at least half a minute.
</P>
<P>
Earthquakes with a magnitude of four to five on the Richter
scale are unlikely to cause damage, but are felt generally by
people indoors and by few people outdoors.
</P>
<P>
Seismologists say the Philippines is hit by an average of six
earthquakes every day but most of them are too weak to be felt.
</P>
</TEXT>
