<HEADLINE> Iran Seizes Over 1,000 Kilograms of Narcotics </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, May 27 (Xinhua) -- Some 1,100 kilograms of narcotic
drugs were seized Wednesday night in Iran's southeastern province
of Sistan-Baluchestan, a senior Iranian security official
announced Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The provincial commander Brigadier General Naser Shabani said
the drugs, consisting of opium and hashish, were seized following
a gun fight between security forces and armed smugglers in the Lar
border region, some 30 kilometers southeast of the provincial
capital Zahedan, the Islamic Republic News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Iranian security forces also seized 5,300 kilograms of narcotic
drugs Monday following armed clashes with drug traffickers in the
province, which borders Afghanistan and Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
Shabani said Tuesday that 9,365 kilograms of various narcotics
have been seized from smugglers in the province since the outset
of the current Iranian calendar year starting March 21.
</P>
<P>
Earlier reports said Iran seized over 195 tons of various
narcotics over the last Iranian calendar year which ended March 20.
</P>
<P>
Iran initiated a strict anti-drug campaign in 1989 after the
Majlis (parliament) passed a law allowing capital punishment
against drug criminals. 
</P>
</TEXT>
