<HEADLINE> Palestinians End Sit-in in East Jerusalem </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, May 27 (Xinhua) -- Dozens of Palestinians ended
their sit-in Thursday afternoon at Ras Al-Amud in East Jerusalem
after the Israeli police released four participants who were
arrested and beaten earlier.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinians staged the sit-in from Thursday morning to
protest against Israel's housing construction at Ras Al-Amud and
the Palestinian protestors clashed with Israeli police who tried
to intervene.
</P>
<P>
Palestinian National Authority (PNA) Minister for Jerusalem
Affairs Faisal Husseini, members of the Palestinian Legislative
Council (PLC) Hanan Ashrawi and Hatem Abdel Qader, as well as
several Israeli Arab Knesset (parliament) members participated in
the sit-in.
</P>
<P>
All above mentioned VIPs and other Palestinian prostetors were
subjected to violence and abuse by the Israeli police during the
scuffle which occurred shortly after noon.
</P>
<P>
During the scuffle, four Palestinians, including Ashrawi's
bodyguard, were arrested, while several others, including local
journalists working for foreign media, were injured.
</P>
<P>
Qader and another PLC member Ahmad Al-Batsh, were admitted to
Makassed Hospital for injury treatment.
</P>
<P>
Qader told reporters later that in the attack, the Israeli
police used rubber clubs and rifle butts to beat the participants
and he said he did not understand why the Israeli police reacted
so violently towards the Palestinians who conducted their sit-in
peacefully.
</P>
<P>
"We consider constructing the settlement there (in Ras
Al-Amud) as a criminal act, every settlement activity is a
criminal act and we will continue our efforts to halt such
activities," he said.
</P>
<P>
Ras Al Amud is a "hot spot" in East Jerusalem. Local
Palestinians refuse to let the Israeli right-wing groups to build
any new house there. 
</P>
</TEXT>
