<BODY>
<HEADLINE> British Judge Turns Down Pinochet Appeal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, May 27 (Xinhua) -- A British High Court on Thursday
refused a permission to challenge the extradition of Former
Chilean leader Augusto Pinochet.
</P>
<P>
Justice Harry Ognall in the High Court ruled that hearing an
appeal at this stage would "go only needlessly to disrupt the
extradition process."
</P>
<P>
"It would be wrong for me to grant permission for judicial
review in this case," Ognall said.
</P>
<P>
Pinochet's lawyers lodged an appeal to the high court for
reviewing the British government's decision to allow extradition
proceedings against the retired general. They argued that Home
Secretary Jack Straw "misdirected himself in law and acted
irrationally" in authorizing proceedings against Pinochet.
</P>
<P>
The lawyers also argued that Jack Straw had not properly
considered all factors in the case, especially whether the charges
remaining against Pinochet amounted to extradition crimes.
</P>
<P>
Ognall meanwhile said lawyers for Pinochet would have "every
opportunity to advance his case" in the extradition hearing yet to
come.
</P>
<P>
Pinochet, 83, was arrested in London on October 16 last year at
the request of a Spanish judge, who wants to try him on torture
allegations dating from his 1973-1990 rule in Chile.
</P>
<P>
British Law Lords, the highest court in Britain, ruled out in
March that Pinochet was responsible for the crimes committed in
Chile, but only in the period from 1988 to 1990. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
