<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pakistan Shoots Down 2 Indian Mig Fighters </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, May 27 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan Thursday shot down two
Indian Mig jet fighters that "crossed into its territory" along
the disputed Kashmir border.
</P>
<P>
Pakistani Information Minister Mushahid Hussain on Thursday
afternoon confirmed the downing of Indian jets at a special joint
press conference here, which was also attended by Vice Chief of
General Staff Lt. General Anis Bajwa, Director General of
Inter-Service Public Relations Brigadier Rashid Qureshi and
Foreign Office Spokesman Tariq Altaf.
</P>
<P>
The first jet was shot down at 11:15 a.m. local time (0615
GMT) and the second at 11:35 a.m. local time (0635 GMT), Mushahid
said.
</P>
<P>
The two jets, one Mig-21 and the other Mig-27, were targeted in
the second round of India's air operations in the Line of Control
region on Thursday, the second day of an air campaign to dislodge
Pakistan-backed militants from the Indian side of the LoC.
</P>
<P>
The first round of Thursday's air operations was carried out in
early morning.
</P>
<P>
The wreckage of the two fighters fell into the
Pakistan-controlled part of Kashmir. One pilot was killed and the
other captured, according to Mushahid.
</P>
<P>
India, however, had said its air force jets had restricted
operations to the Indian side only.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the press conference, Altaf charged that "it was
India and not Pakistan which was escalating the situation."
</P>
<P>
"We call upon our friends and the international community to
realize the situation and impress upon India to observe restraint
so that the situation does not get out of hand," he said.
</P>
<P>
"Meaningful international engagement is an absolute necessity,"
he added.
</P>
<P>
He said, "We hope India would realize that the volatile
situation was brought to an end."
</P>
<P>
India had been continuously refusing to accept any help from
abroad to settle the core issue of Jammu and Kashmir, he said.
</P>
<P>
Tension between Pakistan and India is mounting these days
because of the intense artillery dual that has been going on
uninterrupted for more than two weeks along the LoC in Kashmir.
</P>
<P>
At least 35 soldiers are reported to have been killed along
with scores of civilians on both sides in the renewed clashes in
Kargil and Drass sectors of the LoC which divides the Kashmir
region between the two neighbors.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan Wednesday blamed India for escalating the conflict
through launching air strikes against Kashmiris and said it will
take "all necessary actions" to defend its positions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
