<HEADLINE> Russia Says U.S. Defense Bill Undermines ABM Treaty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, May 27 (Xinhua) -- Russia said Thursday that the U.S.
Congress' approval of a bill to deploy a national anti-missile
defense system is "another step aimed at undermining" the 1972
Soviet-U.S. Anti-Ballistic Missile Treaty.
</P>
<P>
The move represented "a challenge to strategic stability and
international security," the Interfax news agency quoted a Russian
Foreign Ministry statement as saying.
</P>
<P>
The bill "reasserts the U.S. military-political course toward
putting in place nationwide, effective anti-missile defense making
it possible to ensure within the shortest possible time from the
technological point of view U.S. protection against a limited
ballistic attack," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
The 1972 ABM Treaty prohibits the deployment of any anti-
missile defense system on a country's territory, the document
said.
</P>
<P>
"By pursuing the course toward the creation and deployment of
an anti-missile defense system on its territory, the United States
is ignoring the view of the absolute majority of world states
justly discerning in such a policy a direct threat to global
security and stability," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
It said Washington "by its ABM actions stimulates the
emergence and global spread of more advanced missiles (and
contributes) to unleashing a new arms race.
</P>
<P>
"Moreover, such actions can lead to the destruction of the
developed structure of treaties and agreements in the field of
strategic offensive and defensive arms," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. actions "threaten the whole disarmament process,
including the preservation and consolidation of the key regimes of
the non-proliferation of weapons of mass destruction and their
means of trade," the document said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
