President and caretaker Prime Minister Girija Prasad Koirala said
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
In a farewell message read over Radio Nepal, Koirala expressed
the hope that the Communist Party of Nepal (Unified
Marxist-Leninist, CPN-UML), which comes as the second largest
party in the House of Representatives, would succeed in playing
the role of "responsible opposition."
</P>
<P>
Koirala was named in December 1998 to head a tripartite
government to oversee the general elections in May. Krishna Prasad
Bhattarai, a senior leader of the Nepali Congress, was appointed
Thursday to head the new government.
</P>
<P>
In his message to the Nepalese people, Koirala extended his
best wishes to the new government. Months before the elections
held on May 3 and May 17, Koirala had offered the post-poll
premiership to Bhattarai in a bid to patch up dissension with the
party. He said last week that he would extend full cooperation to
the new prime minister.
</P>
<P>
Koirala said the new government has to work on the line of
development, security and employment as mentioned in the party's
election manifesto.
</P>
<P>
He said that despite doubts and apprehensions, the elections
were held without any problem. He described this as a "pleasant
achievement." 
