<HEADLINE> China Improves Service for Small Businesses (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 27 (Xinhua) -- China is introducing overseas funds
and expertise to provide much-needed management training for its
ten million small and medium-sized businesses.
</P>
<P>
The State Economic and Trade Commission (SETC) launched a
showcase training program on information technology for small
businesses here today funded by China Hewlett-Packard Co. Ltd.
</P>
<P>
The 21st Century Small and Medium-sized Enterprises Training
and Development Project will offer training courses to managers of
25 small businesses around China, including private, state-owned,
and overseas-funded companies, most of which are in the
manufacturing sector.
</P>
<P>
"Offering training services to more than ten million small
businesses in China requires so many resources that the government
cannot do it alone," said Wang Zhongming, director of the Training
Department of SETC.
</P>
<P>
"We must tap all possible resources, including overseas funds,
to build up a service network for small businesses in with respect
to training, consultation, and research and development," he said.
</P>
<P>
Wei Dong, director of the Department of Small and Medium-sized
Enterprises of SETC, said that Hewllet-Packard's funding of the
training program opens a new area of improving government services
for small businesses.
</P>
<P>
China Hewlett-Packard, the local branch of U.S.-based Hewlett-
Packard, has previously sponsored management training programs for
large state-owned businesses in China.
</P>
</TEXT>
