<BODY>
<HEADLINE> WFP Launches Telecom Team to Facilitate Service </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, May 27 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations World Food
Program (WFP) Thursday launched a service aimed at improving field
communications through a specialist team of experts.
</P>
<P>
The team, a Fast Information Technology and Telecommunications
Emergency and Support Team, is based in Kampala, Uganda's capital,
according to a press release issued by the agency's Uganda office.
</P>
<P>
The team will work primarily to enhance rapid response capacity
 throughout sub-Sahara Africa by extending and improving the flow
of information in the field wherever an emergency demands that
operational and security data be quickly and reliably
communicated.
</P>
<P>
The statement quoted Peter Casier, technical support unit
manager at WFP Great Lakes, as saying that "Communication is
crucial in any aid operation. We need to know about people's
condition, their needs, and how we can reach them."
</P>
<P>
"In many parts of Africa, the telephone lines are either
extremely bad or non-existent. Using short wave radio has proved
not only more cost effective, but also much more reliable," the
manager added.
</P>
<P>
The WFP Great Lakes Unit sealed its global reputation for rapid
response in the wake of Hurricane Mitch, when it was despatched to
Central America to set up a voice and data communications network,
serving not only the WFP, but also the U.N. agencies and partners.
</P>
<P>
In 1995, at the peak of the Rwanda/Zaire/Burundi relief
operation, a small team of technicians in the WFP Great Lakes Unit
devised the innovative Deep Field Mailing System, using HF radios
to transfer e-mails independently from electricity or telephone
lines at very low cost.
</P>
<P>
This communications revolution now covers an area of two
million square kilometers, linking up 2,000 users from 15
different U.N. agencies and non- governmental organizations in 100
bases and cars, processing over 200,000 e-mails per month.
</P>
<P>
The WFP is the U.N. front-line agency in the fight against
global hunger.
</P>
<P>
Last year, its relief workers fed 75 million people, including
most of the world's refugees. Headquartered in Rome, Italy, WFP
has food aid operations in 80 countries around the world. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
