<HEADLINE> International Aid Agency Concerned About Situation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, May 27 (Xinhua) -- The Somali Aid Coordination Body
(SACB) is deeply concerned with rapidly deteriorating situation
in southern Somalia, particularly over the reported recent
arrival of arms into the country.
</P>
<P>
The aid body, comprising donors, U.N. agencies and
international non- governmental organizations, reaffirmed its
commitment to continue providing humanitarian assistance to the
needed in Somalia, according to a press release available here
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
As a consequence to the increase in banditry and general
instability, the release said, it has become increasingly
difficult for international aid agencies to access vulnerable
communities in southern Somalia.
</P>
<P>
"The notable expansion of incident against international aid
agencies, with two aid workers having been murdered and another
kidnapped already this year, is of utmost concern," the release
added.
</P>
<P>
While reiterating its commitment, the SACB appeals to the
Somali leaders and communities in general, especially in southern
areas, to facilitate the work of international aid agencies to
continue carrying out their humanitarian work by ensuring
security conditions for their staff and assets.
</P>
<P>
The SACB also urged the relevant international organizations to
 encourage a peace process that would lead to reconciliation in
Somalia and ask for their renewed support in this endeavour.
</P>
