<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Two Major Hospitals in Somali Capital Looted </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOGADISHU, May 27 (Xinhua) -- After nine years of anarchy and
civil strife in Somalia, the destruction in the capital Mogadishu
still continues despite relative peace due to the existence of
Islamic courts militiamen who control the major parts of South
Mogadishu.
</P>
<P>
The main hospitals of Martini and Digfer, both in South
Mogadishu, have been crippled after they were looted of their most
 precious equipment last week.
</P>
<P>
Ali Robleh Warfa, director of Martini hospital, told the press
 Thursday that his hospital has been looted and that apart from
the building nothing of use has remained.
</P>
<P>
Warfa said the main operational theatre for both the major and
ordinary surgery including the ophthalmic has been totally
ransacked and taken away.
</P>
<P>
In addition, more than 12,000 pieces of the internal fixation
plates worth of 50,000 U.S. dollars have also been looted.
</P>
<P>
"Those plates have been used for all kinds of fractures from a
finger to the major bones of the body," said Warfa, adding that
they have got their equipment from Switzerland.
</P>
<P>
He said seven new sets of operational utensils worth of more
than 7,000 dollars had also been stolen.
</P>
<P>
Dozens of war crippled people including children and women,
families from the former police and military live in the hospital,
some for treatment, others take it as residential quarter.
</P>
<P>
Many of the crippled have expressed concern after the only
hospital on which they depended had been stolen of its equipment.
"It is really unfortunate that our hospital which survived the
worst part of the civil war now becomes among the victims of the
anarchy," said one crippled man.
</P>
<P>
The general hospital known as Digfer, the biggest in Somalia,
has also been looted. Mohamed Hussein Abdi, the director of
Digfer hospital, has declared that his hospital can no longer
operate after its modern German- donated X-ray apparatus has been
looted.
</P>
<P>
Independent sources confirmed that the X-ray has been put in a
house in Huriwa district of South Mogadishu controlled by faction
leader Hussein Mohamed Aidid.
</P>
<P>
In the beginning of the anarchy, some unscrupulous businessmen
had looted the country to the teeth by taking away all of the
major factories and sold them abroad. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
