<HEADLINE> China to Strike Hard on Crime Targeting Disabled </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 27 (Xinhua) -- The Ministry of Public Security
said today that China will intensify the strike against crime
targeting disabled people in an effort to protect the legitimate
rights of the disabled.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that "police will focus their attention on such
criminal activities as maiming the disabled, abducting and trading
disabled women and children, raping disabled women, and forcing
disabled women to act as prostitutes."
</P>
<P>
It has been reported that police broke up a major crime ring
in the city of Xuzhou in east China's Jiangsu Province who were
preying on disabled persons. To date, local police have detained
three criminal suspects and rescued nine deaf-mute young women.
</P>
<P>
The official disclosed that the State Council Coordination
Committee for the Work of the Disabled Persons sent a letter to
the Ministry of Public Security recently calling on the national
police force to strike hard at crimes targeting the disabled, and
provide better services for the disabled while protecting their
rights and interests in accordance with law. 
</P>
