<HEADLINE> 4 Kurdish Rebels Killed in Southeastern Turkey </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, May 27 (Xinhua) -- Four rebels of the illegal Kurdish
Workers' Party (PKK) Thursday were killed in a military operation
staged by the Turkish security forces in southeastern Turkey, the
semi-official Anatolia News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The agency said that acting on a tip-off, the security forces
besieged a group of the PKK militants near Baspinar village in
Kemaliye town of Erzincan province and exchanged fires with the
PKK.
</P>
<P>
The security forces killed four PKK guerrillas in the armed
clash, the report said, adding that three soldiers of the security
forces were slightly wounded.
</P>
<P>
The agency reported that the death toll of the PKK militants
may increase in the clash.
</P>
<P>
The PKK has been fighting since 1984 for an independent
Kurdish state in southeastern Turkey. Conflicts between the
Turkish government and the PKK have claimed over 37,000 lives.
</P>
<P>
PKK leader Abdullah Ocalan was captured by Turkish special
agents in Kenya in mid-February and has been detained on Imrali
Island in Marmara Sea near Turkey's western province of Bursa for
trials on charges of treason. 
</P>
</TEXT>
