<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Over 400,000 Ugandans Receive HIV/AIDS Tests Since </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, May 27 (Xinhua) -- Over 400,000 Ugandans have tested
for HIV/ AIDS at the AIDS Information Center (AIC) sites in the
country's districts of Kampala, Mbarara, Mbale and Jinja since
1990.
</P>
<P>
The information is released by a national HIV/AIDS voluntary
counselling and testing symposium held at the International
Conference Center here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
According to the figures released by the AIDS Information
Center, a total of 53,854 people have received voluntary
counselling and testing in 1998 alone, six times more than in
1990.
</P>
<P>
Among those tested, two thirds were female in 1990 and now the
female- male ratio is 1:1.
</P>
<P>
The Information Center has expanded voluntary counselling and
testing to 41 government and non-governmental organization
hospitals and health centers in 21 districts of Uganda.
</P>
<P>
As a result of the establishment of testing facilities,
Uganda's seropositivity rate has dropped significantly. The
HIV-positive rate for female has fallen from over 35 percent eight
years ago to the current level of 27 percent while that for male
decreased from 24 percent to 15 percent over the same period.
</P>
<P>
The Center findings also show that females are more vulnerable
to the epidemic than males. Divorced and separated females are
extremely viable to be infected.
</P>
<P>
The vulnerability to the disease is highly related to one's
level of education. The illiterate are mostly likely to suffer.
About 28 percent of male and 40 percent of female in this category
prove to be HIV positive while of those who have received
secondary education, the rates drop to 13 percent and 21 percent
respectively.
</P>
<P>
The symposium called upon people, young people in particular,
to go and test, because it is good for themselves and for the
society in general. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990527.0103 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-27 </DATE_TIME>
