<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AIDS Patients in China to Receive Cocktail Therapy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 27 (Xinhua) -- Combination therapy against HIV/
AIDS, known as "cocktail therapy," is being introduced in China to
treat AIDS patients since the state drug authorities approved
imports of anti-HIV drugs.
</P>
<P>
The National Center for AIDS Prevention and Control (NCAIDS)
and Ditan Hospital in Beijing announced they will provide triple-
drug therapy to 18 carriers of HIV (human immunodeficiency virus)
that causes AIDS ( acquired immune deficiency syndrome) in mid-
June, and to 12 others late this year.
</P>
<P>
The State Drug Administration has given approval to the import
of six types of anti-HIV drugs since late 1997. The SDA even
allowed the entry of drugs which did not undergo long-term
clinical tests because their effectiveness was confirmed, and
domestic patients have urgent needs, a SDA official told Xinhua
today.
</P>
<P>
Some foreign pharmaceutical firms have applied for
certification from the SDA, and their products may be available
this year or next, the official said.
</P>
<P>
Although the number of treated patients is far less than the
400,000 people infected by HIV nationwide, the majority of whom
have little access to effective medication, NCAIDS experts believe
this new action will bring about greater availability of such
service.
</P>
<P>
"It has become very urgent to provide proper and effective
treatment against HIV/AIDS in China since the epidemic situation
is getting serious," said Professor Cao Yunzhen, deputy director
of the NCAIDS.
</P>
<P>
Though combination therapy can keep the virus at bay, its price
is dear -- at about 100,000 yuan ( 12,000 U.S. dollars) for a
year's course. Few patients in China can afford the treatment.
</P>
<P>
"The money is the biggest problem. But we're making every
effort to help the patients, whether through raising funds by
patients themselves or asking help from pharmaceutical companies
and charity groups."
</P>
<P>
"The most important thing is to act right now to save their
lives. It's also a key measure to block the further spread of the
virus," said Prof. Cao, who has worked in the United States at the
Aaron Diamond AIDS Research Center led by Professor David Ho,
known as one of the originators of the "cocktail therapy."
</P>
<P>
Cao, now in charge of clinical virology research at NCAIDS and
a clinic at Ditan Hospital, said training medical personnel across
the country is also important.
</P>
<P>
A training course will be offered by NCAIDS this October to
help doctors from all over the country master the complicated
triple-drug treatment.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, clinical research combining Western medicine
and traditional Chinese herbal medicines will be conducted to see
whether the human immune system can be restored while clearing HIV
in the blood.
</P>
<P>
If successful, it will be a special contribution by the Chinese
to the battle against HIV/AIDS, Cao said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990527.0109 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine Senate Ratifies VFA </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, May 27 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine Senate ratified
Thursday evening the Philippines-U.S. Visiting Forces Agreement
(VFA) by a vote of 18 for and 5 against.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, thousands of protesters rallied in the rain outside
the senate building against the ratification of the controversial
pact.
</P>
<P>
A survey conduct by SNN TV Thursday showed that nearly 60
percent Filipinos are against the VFA.
</P>
<P>
Under the Philippine Constitution, the VFA needs at least 16
votes or two-thirds of the 23-member senate to be ratified.
</P>
<P>
The VFA, which was signed by Philippine and U.S. officials last
year, would allow the United States to resume major ship visits
and large-scale joint war exercises in the Philippines which were
suspended in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Supporters say the VFA will help protect regional peace and
stability and strengthen the Philippine Armed Forces as well as
the political, economic and security linkages with the United
states.
</P>
<P>
But critics say the pact would limit the Philippine
government's right to prosecute American soldiers who commit
crimes in the country, promote prostitution and drag the
Philippines into conflicts with enemies of the United States.
</P>
<P>
In recent weeks, protesters have held almost daily
demonstrations in front of the Philippine Senate and the U.S.
Embassy.
</P>
<P>
The two largest rebel groups, National Democratic Front (NDF)
and Moro Islamic Liberation Front (MILF), in the Philippines have
threatened to terminate peace talks with the government if the VFA
is ratified, saying the accord would negate their future demands
for reforms.
</P>
<P>
The Philippines signed a Mutual Defense Treaty with Washington
in 1951. Officials in both countries say joint exercises are
needed to ensure good cooperation and communication between the
armed forces of the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Military ties with the United States, which ruled the
Philippines for nearly half a century, have remained a sensitive
issue since the Philippine Senate forced the closure of the last
U.S. base in 1992. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990527.0110 </DOCNO>
