<DOCNO> XIE19990527.0112 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Space Shuttle Discovery Blasts Off </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, May 27 (Xinhua) -- With seven astronauts on board,
the U.S. NASA's space shuttle Discovery was lifted off this
morning at 6:50 (local time) from the Kennedy Space Center, Cape
Canaveral, for the first docking with the constructing
International Space Station in orbit.
</P>
<P>
During its 10-day flight which is the first one since last
December, the space shuttle will dock with the international space
station for six days and crew members of the seven astronauts will
unload more than 4,300 pounds of cargo for the space station.
</P>
<P>
The supplies include laptop computers, cameras, canvas bags of
maintenance tools, two cranes and seven 95-gallon bags of drinking
water siphoned from the shuttle's electricity-generating fuel
cells. Water is a byproduct of power production.
</P>
<P>
These goods will be carried into the space station for the
first crew, two Russians and an American who will arrive early
next year.
</P>
<P>
During the visit, two astronauts will walk in space for a day
to mount parts of two construction cranes, one made in the United
States and the other in Russia, to their respective components.
Members of the crew will also try to repair a Russian power
storage system and an American communication system on the space
station. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
