<HEADLINE> India Admits Loosing 2 Fighter Jets in Kashmir </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, May 27 (Xinhua) -- Indian Defense Ministry sources
Thursday admitted that India lost two fighter jets during
Thursday's air operation in the disputed Kashmir area and one of
them was shot down by Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
They said two Indian Air Force (IAF) Mig fighter jets were lost
in the operations against "Pakistani infiltrators" in the Kargil
sector of Kashmir, one of which was shot down by a Pakistani
missile and the other had a technical snag.
</P>
<P>
A Mig-21 aircraft had engine failure while participating in the
fourth round of strikes at around 11:00 local time. The pilot gave
a distress call as he ejected from the plane, Air Vice Marshal
Malik said here.
</P>
<P>
As a Mig-27 jet which received the call flew low to locate the
pilot of Mig-21 aircraft, it was fired at from across the Line of
Control by a surface-to-air missile, he said.
</P>
<P>
This was a "hostile and provocative act as we were operating
within the Indian territory close to the Line of Control. The
other side has escalated the situation," he said.
</P>
<P>
Following this, extraordinary measures were being taken and the
operation against the infiltration would continue, he said. But he
did not elaborate on the extraordinary measures India was taking.
</P>
