<HEADLINE> EDS-Russia-Belgrade Envoy Trip to Belgrade Delayed, Talks Hit Snag </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, May 27 (Xinhua) -- Russian envoy Viktor Chernomyrdin's
planned trip to Belgrade was delayed Thursday when the protracted
talks on Yugoslavia attended by the envoy, U.S. Deputy Secretary
of State Strobe Talbott and Finnish President Martti Ahtisaari hit
a new snag in Moscow.
</P>
<P>
The sides, which took a break to consult with their experts
and advisers, will resume the talks late Thursday, the Itar-Tass
news agency quoted Chernomyrdin's adviser Valentin Sergeyev as
saying.
</P>
<P>
The latest round of tripartite talks started Wednesday and
might well stretch into the night Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Sergeyev said Chernomyrdin's trip to Belgrade Thursday was
still on, but his departure was delayed.
</P>
<P>
"All depends on when the talks end," Sergeyev said.
</P>
<P>
He acknowledged that the talks were proceeding with difficulty
but added, "this is a normal process for such a sophisticated
issue."
</P>
<P>
"A precipitate decision does not meet anyone's interests," he
said.
</P>
<P>
In a related development, Chernomyrdin on Thursday reiterated
Moscow's threat to pull out of the talks if NATO bombings on
Yugoslavia did not end soon.
</P>
<P>
In an article published in The Washington Post, Chernomyrdin
said NATO should end the air campaign because it was impossible to
negotiate a peace settlement when the bombs were falling.
</P>
<P>
"I shall advise Russia's president (Boris Yeltsin) to suspend
Russian participation in the negotiating process, put an end to
all military-technological cooperation with the United States and
Western Europe, put off the ratification of START II and use
Russia's veto as the United Nations debates a resolution on
Yugoslavia," Chernomyrdin said.
</P>
<P>
He expressed confidence that on this issue Russia would "find
understanding from great powers such as China and India."
</P>
<P>
Chernomyrdin said NATO's air strikes on Yugoslavia, which
entered the 65th day Thursday, had "set back Russia-U.S. relations
by several decades."
</P>
<P>
He refuted a statement by U.S. President Bill Clinton that
Russia was allegedly helping NATO to make Belgrade meet its
conditions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
