<HEADLINE> Pakistan Shoots Down 2 Indian Mig Fighters </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, May 27 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan Thursday claimed to have
shot down two Indian Mig-27 jet fighters that it said had crossed
into its territory along the disputed Kashmir border.
</P>
<P>
The first jet was shot down at 11:15 a.m. local time (0615 GMT)
and the second at 11:35 p.m. local time (0635 GMT), military
sources said.
</P>
<P>
The two jets were targeted in the second round of India's air
operations in the Line of Control (LoC) region Thursday, the
second day of an air campaign to dislodge Pakistan-backed
militants from the Indian side of the LoC.
</P>
<P>
The first round of Thursday's air operations was carried out in
the early morning.
</P>
<P>
The wreckage of the two fighters fell into the
Pakistan-controlled part of Kashmir. One pilot was killed and the
other captured, according to Pakistani Information Minister
Mushahid Hussain.
</P>
<P>
India said its air force jets had restricted operations to the
Indian side only, but Pakistan claimed that Indian aircraft had
intruded into Pakistani territory.
</P>
<P>
Tension between the two estranged South Asian neighbors has
been mounting these days because of the intense artillery dual
that has been going on uninterrupted for more than two weeks along
the LoC in Kashmir.
</P>
<P>
At least 35 soldiers are reported to have been killed along
with scores of civilians on both sides in the renewed clash in
Kargil and Drass sectors of the LoC which divides the Kashmir
region between the two neighbors.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan Wednesday blamed India for escalating the conflict
through launching air strikes against Kashmiris and said it would
take "all necessary actions" to defend its positions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
