<HEADLINE> Jezzine Pullback Not Signal of Israeli Withdrawal: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, May 27 (Xinhua) -- The planned evacuation of a South
Lebanon Army (SLA) battalion in the Jezzine Enclave in southern
Lebanon was not a signal of a large withdrawal of Israeli troops,
an Israeli officer said on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Israel Radio quoted Shaul Mofaz, Israeli army chief of general
staff, as saying that the decision to pullback the Israeli-backed
SLA militiamen from Jezzine was made by SLA commander Antoin Lahad.
</P>
<P>
Mofaz stressed that the pullback was not linked to Israeli
Prime Minister-elect Ehud Barak's plan to withdraw Israeli troops
from southern Lebanon within one year.
</P>
<P>
He noted that Israel would deliberate the strategic steps of
withdrawal according to the negotiations at the political level
and the army's assessment of situation.
</P>
<P>
In 1985, Israel set up a "security zone" in its occupied
southern Lebanon allegedly to protect its northern border areas
from being attacked by Lebanese guerrillas.
</P>
<P>
Since then, Lebanese resistance forces spearheaded by the
Hezbollah, or Party of God, has been fighting to oust Israeli
occupation troops and the SLA from the territory.
</P>
<P>
Barak has pledged that he would soon resume peace talks with
Lebanon and Syria in order to withdraw the Israeli troops from
southern Lebanon in a year.
</P>
<P>
The Jezzine enclave is situated at the extreme north of the
"security zone" with about 170 SLA soldiers stationed there.
</P>
<P>
Local daily Haaretz quoted the Israeli defense sources as
saying on Thursday that Lahad initiated the idea to withdraw from
Jezzine after several senior SLA officers were killed or wounded
there in Lebanese guerrilla attacks over the past few weeks.
</P>
<P>
The sources added that the pullback from Jezzine could be
completed within a few weeks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
