<DOCNO> XIE19990527.0121 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Man Recovers From 170-Day Coma </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANJING, May 27 (Xinhua) -- A Chinese man who was in a coma for
more than 170 days has regained consciousness in a hospital in the
city of Nanjing, capital of east China's Jiangsu Province.
</P>
<P>
Han Ping, a farmer in Jiangsu, was brought back to
consciousness on May 24 by the electric impulse therapy and can
now talk.
</P>
<P>
Han had suffered a serious traumatic head injury in an accident
last December, that left him in a coma.
</P>
<P>
In February this year, he was sent to the China Brain Recovery
Center based in Nanjing for further treatment.
</P>
<P>
Doctors in the center treated him with hyperbaric oxygenation
for over three months to help him take a change for the better,
and then decided to use the electric impulse therapy.
</P>
<P>
A three-centimeter-long electrode was fixed in Han's spinal
column near the neck during an operation on May 22. A remote
sensor was used to send electric impulses through the electrode at
regular intervals to stimulate his spinal nerves.
</P>
<P>
Han became conscious 40 hours after the operation.
</P>
<P>
In the past three years, the center has treated more than 100
persons who were in a coma, with about 80 of them regaining some
feeling in their limbs.
</P>
<P>
About 100,000 people become comatose in China every year
because of a variety of accidents.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990527.0122 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Siberian Tiger Shows up in Northeastern Mountain </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGCHUN, May 27 (Xinhua) -- An endangered Siberian tiger
showed up again in Changbai Mountains recently, attacking and
eating livestock in this northeastern mountain area.
</P>
<P>
Animal experts investigated the incident and concluded from the
footprints around two slain horses that it was done by a Siberian
tiger.
</P>
<P>
The most recent incident occurred May 13 when farmer Wang
Jianqiu in Jiaohe City found one of his horses seriously bitten.
The horse later died, and two other horses were missing.
</P>
<P>
Wang searched for his horses in nearby the forests and
discovered their bodies eight days later.
</P>
<P>
A provincial forest official said this is not the first time a
Siberian tiger has attacked domestic animals this year. In the
neighboring Dunhua area, farmers have reported tigers eating their
cattle last winter and this May.
</P>
<P>
The Siberian tiger is listed by the World Wild Fund for Nature
as one of the ten most-endangered animal species in the world, and
only around 300 of them still survive.
</P>
<P>
A UN-funded field investigation by scientists from China,
Russia, and the United States found that no more than 20 Siberian
tigers are now living in the mountains of northeastern China.
</P>
<P>
More than 20 incidents have been reported of Siberian tigers
eating livestock such as horses and cattle, most of them in
Changbai Mountains, a major habitat for the tiger. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
