<HEADLINE> Chinese Tibetan Team Scale Mt. Qomolangma (Repeat) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LHASA, May 27 (Xinhua) -- A 10-member Tibetan team Thursday
successfully scaled Mount Qomolangma, the world's highest peak, in
an unprecedented adventure to gather the flame for a national
games.
</P>
<P>
The flame, which is to ignite the main cauldron of the 6th
Chinese National Ethnic Games in Lhasa this August, was lit on
the 8,848-meter summit.
</P>
<P>
The team launched the ascent at 3:00 a.m. from a 8,300 meters
camp. Benba Zaxi became the first climber of the team to conquer
Qomolangma when he set foot on the peak at 8:02 a.m. after four
hours and 47 minutes.
</P>
<P>
The other climbers -- Cering Doje, Rigna, Loze, Akabo, Gambo,
Lhaba, Zaxi Gering and women adventurers Gusang and Gigi, all
reached the summit within an hour after Benba Zaxi's successful
climb. It was the quickest time ever recorded for a climbing team.
</P>
<P>
Gusang became the first Chinese woman to surmount Mt.
Qunolangma twice and Rigna and Gigi the first-ever Chinese couple
to reach the peak, said team captain Samzu.
</P>
<P>
Today's feat also made Benba Zaxi a joint holder of a Chinese
mountaineering record with Cering Doje and Rigna. All three
climbers have scaled 10 above-8000 meters mountains. 
</P>
</TEXT>
