<HEADLINE> S. Leone Govt Rejects Rebels' Call for Interim </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, May 27 (Xinhua) -- The Sierra Leonean government has
rejected a call by the rebel Revolutionary United Front (RUF) for
a four-year transition government, Nigeria's The Guardian
newspaper reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted an official document of the Sierra Leonean
government as saying that "the government lacks the power to
accede to the RUF's proposal for the setting up of a transitional
government in place of the present government."
</P>
<P>
The Sierra leonean government has also rejected a proposal for
a new constitution, although it would consider amending the
current one, according to the document outlining Freetown's
position on bringing peace to the war-ravaged west African
country.
</P>
<P>
The document was released for the peace talks between Sierra
Leonean President Ahmed Tejan Kabbah and the rebel RUF held in
Togolese capital Lome Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted Sierra Leonean Foreign Minister Sam Banya as
saying in Lome Wednesday that his government must "remain firm on
constitutional matters because that is what democracy and good
governance is all about."
</P>
<P>
"We can't just treat the law like a piece of paper and throw it
away anytime we like," the minister stressed.
</P>
<P>
According to the document, the government will not hesitate to
free rebel leader Foday Sankoh, but will only do so "within the
judicial and constitutional process."
</P>
<P>
President Kabbah has said that Sankoh, who was sentenced to
death on treason charges last October, could be released only
after his death sentence appeal is heard in court.
</P>
<P>
The government also agreed that a proposal for amnesty for RUF
members would be examined, taking into consideration "gross human
rights violations committed against the citizens of this country."
</P>
<P>
The Freetown government has sent an eight-member delegation
headed by Attorney General Solomon Berewa to the talks while a
10-member delegation from rebel RUF is in Lome.
</P>
<P>
Since the rebel forces launched attacks in several parts of the
country Monday, calm has prevailed for two days and a cease-fire
agreement seemed to be holding in Sierra Leone. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
