<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shanghai to Clean Major River </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, May 27 (Xinhua) -- The first phase of a major program
to clean up the Suzhou River in China's leading industrial and
commercial city of Shanghai has just received state approval and
is expected to start soon.
</P>
<P>
Scheduled to be completed by 2002 the project will cost 8.65
billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
The money will mainly be used to improve the quality of the
river water in the city and plant trees covering an area of 855 sq
km along the river banks.
</P>
<P>
The first 10 elements in the initial phase will include the
construction of sewage disposal plants and river dredging.
</P>
<P>
Additional pump stations will also be built to increase the
river's water volume to improve the natural filtration process.
</P>
<P>
The 120-kilometer-long Suzhou River had an abundance of fish in
the last century, when fishing by the riverbank was one of the ten
major scenic views in old Shanghai, but it became seriously
polluted as the city developed its economy.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai began to tackle the river pollution in the 1980s and
reduced polluted water by 1.4 million tons daily.
</P>
<P>
This made a visible change but failed to change the water
quality of the river enough because of a large number of pollution
sources. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990527.0137 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Global Cooperation Needed for New Financial Architecture: HK Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, May 27 (Xinhua) -- Global cooperation to perfect the
international financial architecture is the key to sustaining long-
term growth of the world's financial markets, Rafael Hui, Hong
Kong's secretary for financial services, said here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
This cooperation can allow all countries and regions in the
world to enjoy the full benefits of market liberalization in a
truly globalized world economy, Hui noted at the Financial
Conference on Asia organized by the Hong Kong Trade Development
Council.
</P>
<P>
In his speech entitled "What Follows the Financial Turmoil",
Hui warned that history would repeat itself without the joint
effort of the international community in reforming the global
financial architecture, and formulating new rules and strategies
to cope with the massive and volatile capital flows in the
globalized economy.
</P>
<P>
Noting that rapid increase in the quantity and volatility of
capital flows had led to new problems and challenges in recent
years, Hui said there were indications that the great majority of
foreign exchange transactions were unrelated to genuine commercial
trade or hedging.
</P>
<P>
The lack of definitive data made it difficult to understand
their nature, movements and impact on financial markets and the
real economy.
</P>
<P>
"In light of the potential destabilizing effects of capital
flows, especially on emerging markets, we consider it timely to
review the existing regulatory framework," Hui said.
</P>
<P>
The ultimate objective should be to promote the free flow of
soundly based capital and the smooth-functioning of financial
markets, he said.
</P>
<P>
"We are not advocating capital control. It will be illegal
under the Basic Law," Hui said.
</P>
<P>
"What we are advocating is to enhance the transparency and
surveillance of volatile short term flows," he stressed.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that the lack of transparency and data on some
capital flows had made it very difficult to assess the extent of
overshooting and devastation exacerbated by the activities of the
highly leveraged institutions (HLIs), including hedge funds.
</P>
<P>
Open markets, in particular the smaller ones, can be
overwhelmed by the very large and highly leveraged institutions,
he said.
</P>
<P>
"Experience shows that some HLIs could generate panic in the
market by acting in concert as a pool, sometimes even using means
such as wash sales and rumor-mongering. Market integrity, which is
fundamental to the health and efficiency of a free market, is
compromised," he added.
</P>
<P>
While much of the international efforts in the past 22 months
had been on improving the transparency and accountability of the
public sector, the private sector so far was lagging behind, Hui
said.
</P>
<P>
"The problem is especially highlighted by the lack of
transparency in the over-the-counter market (OTC market), where
geographically dispersed traders are linked to one another via
telecommunications systems and computers," he said.
</P>
<P>
"This has made monitoring and surveillance difficult, thereby
raising the risk of price-ramping, collusion and other misconduct
by the larger players. This information gap may have serious
implications on market integrity and stability of the financial
system," he added.
</P>
<P>
"As long as this gap in our international financial
architecture remains unplugged, our financial system, individually
and collectively, will continue to be vulnerable to manipulative
attacks of one kind or another," he warned.
</P>
<P>
Noting that there were some encouraging recent developments on
the international front to improve transparency of the HLIs, Hui
said he looked forward to early completion of the work of the G7
Financial Stability Forum on HLIs, offshore centers and short-term
capital flows, adding that Hong Kong would continue to play an
active part in all of these endeavors.
</P>
<P>
In Hong Kong, measures had been taken to strengthen the
currency board system and to enhance the transparency and
disclosure in the securities and futures markets. The government
also reaffirmed the plan to consolidate the existing 12 pieces of
securities-related legislation into one, with the intention to
provide a more transparent and coherent regulatory framework and
more effective regulation in an increasingly sophisticated and
fast changing financial market.
</P>
<P>
However, a global problem calls for a global solution, Hui
pointed out. "We call for global cooperation of the industrialized
and emerging economies to perfect international financial
architecture as a matter of urgency," he concluded. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
