<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, May 27 (Xinhua) -- The Australian share market
Thursday defied a hefty rise on Wall Street to end softer,
dragged down by falls in the resources and industrial sectors.
</P>
<P>
The all ordinaries index gave up 13.8 points by the close to
2,904.7.
</P>
<P>
The all industrials index surrendered 17.4 points to 5,135.2
and the all resources index lost 13.6 points to 1,113.4.
</P>
<P>
National turnover on the Australian Stock Exchange reached
477.4 million shares traded worth 921.32 million U.S. dollars.
Falls outpaced rises by 771 to 618 and 490 stocks were steady.
</P>
<P>
The weakness in the local market surprised some brokers
considering Wall Street's two key indices, the Dow Jones
Industrial Average and the S&AMP;P 500, were both up 1.6 percent
Wednesday night to 10,702.1 and 1,304.8 respectively.
</P>
<P>
The Commonwealth Bank of Australia was up 27 cents to 24.72
Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
But the other major banks were mainly lower with Westpac bank
down 17 cents to 10.40 Australian dollars, ANZ bank off eight
cents to 11.18 Australian dollars but National Australia Bank
managed to rise 8.2 cents to 24.93 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
Resource stocks were led lower by another tumble in gold
stocks. The gold sub-index closed 36.1 points down to 847.3.
</P>
<P>
Gold bullion in Sydney closed Thursday at 269.25 U.S. dollars
an ounce compared with Wednesday's close of 270.85 U.S. dollars an
ounce.
</P>
<P>
Diversified mining heavyweight BHP eased 10 cents to 15.80
Australian dollars while global miner Rio Tinto, which warned of
further pressure on commodity prices, shed 55 cents to 22.05
Australian dollars. 
</P>
