<HEADLINE> China Reshuffles Geographical Structure of Grain Growing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 27 (Xinhua) -- The powerful market mechanism has
begun to reshuffle grain production geographically, with more rice
grown in north China and more corn in southern China.
</P>
<P>
Traditionally southern China has to rely on corn from north
China, incurring heavy transportation costs. However, statistics
show that the corn growing area is enlarging south of the Yangtze.
Hunan Province has claimed that it can sufficiently supply itself
corn.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, rice, traditionally mainly grown in southern China,
has seen increased acreage in northeast China. Some 1.2 million ha
of rice is grown in northeast China. The ratio of its rice output
in its total grain output has ascended by over ten percentage
points.
</P>
<P>
The People's Daily reported today that some agricultural
experts are studying for ways to increase corn growing in southern
China. 
</P>
</TEXT>
