<DOCNO> XIE19990527.0153 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia Launches 1 Billion U.S. Dollar Global Bond </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Kuala Lumpur, May 27 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia successfully launched
a 10-year Global Bond in New York amounting to 1.0 billion U.S.
dollars, carrying a coupon rate of 8.75 percent per annum,
reported Bernama news agency here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Announcing the launch Wednesday in a statement, First Finance
Minister Tun Daim Zainuddin said despite difficult market
conditions, the bonds were oversubscribed by 300 percent
reflecting "the confidence of investors in Malaysia's credit
standing and strong prospects of economic recovery."
</P>
<P>
The bonds, due in the year 2009, carry a spread of 330 basis
points over the 10-year U.S. treasury bills. Proceeds from the
bonds would be utilized for general development purposes, said
Daim.
</P>
<P>
"Given the prevailing market conditions and the decline in the
Emerging Market Index, the spread is considered favorable," said
Daim who has been leading a grueling 10-day roadshow covering key
Asian, European and American cities.
</P>
<P>
The bonds were subscribed by 134 high quality investors -- 49
from Asia, 23 from Europe and 62 from the United States. More than
half the value of the bond is held by U.S. account holders, a
quarter by Europeans and the remainder by Asians.
</P>
<P>
Daim said the aim of the issue was to reach as broad as
possible an investor base and to establish a fairly-priced
benchmark for Malaysian bonds.
</P>
<P>
The issue marked a successful return to the global bond market
for the government of Malaysia amidst very difficult market
conditions, he noted.
</P>
<P>
On May 11, Malaysia filed with the U.S. Securities and Exchange
Commission its intention to issue up to 3.0 billion U.S. dollars
in debt securities.
</P>
<P>
The Finance Ministry had initially planned to raise 2.0 billion
dollars, but Wednesday issued 1.0 billion, "taking into account
the widened spreads and the potential for continued unstable
market conditions," said Daim.
</P>
<P>
Second Finance Minister Datuk Mustapa Mohamed said the rest of
the amount could be raised over the next two years or rolled-over
-- affording the Malaysian government the flexibility to do so as
and when necessary.
</P>
<P>
The bonds will be listed and traded in accordance with the
rules of the Luxembourg Stock Exchange and the Stock Exchange of
Hong Kong Limited.
</P>
<P>
Mustapa said Wednesday's successful launch indicated a
"turnaround in investors' perception of Malaysia" since selective
capital and currency control measures were imposed last September
when many doubted that Malaysia would be able to access the
international capital market.
</P>
<P>
"Today's successful issue proved them wrong," said Mustapa.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
