<HEADLINE> Poverty On the Wane in Guangxi </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANNING, May 27 (Xinhua) -- The Yao Autonomous County of Bama
and other 13 counties in south China's Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous
Region announced earlier this week that they have almost
eliminated poverty in their rural areas.
</P>
<P>
Poverty has been eradicated in 47 of the 49 officially defined
poverty-ridden counties in Guangxi, according to a regional
government official.
</P>
<P>
The poverty issue in the remaining two counties, Yao Autonomous
County of Du'an and Yao Autonomous County of Dahua, is expected to
be resolved next year, the official added.
</P>
<P>
China has pledged to eliminate poverty in all rural areas by
the end of this century. Fifteen years ago, Guangxi used to be one
of the country's concentrations of poverty-stricken people, with a
total of 15 million not having enough to eat and wear.
</P>
<P>
Thanks to increased efforts to develop natural resources,
resettle people and export labor services and to greater outside
financing in loans, Guangxi's poverty-stricken population has been
decreasing at a rate of one million each year. By the end of last
year it was down to some three million, the official said.
</P>
<P>
In almost all of the previously destitute counties, the average
annual income of farmers have reached 1,500 yuan and the
illiteracy and semi-illiteracy rate has dropped to less than five
percent, he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
