<DOCNO> XIE19990527.0161 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hegemonism Undermines International Disarmament Process: China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, May 27 (Xinhua) -- The practice of hegemonism, power
politics and "gunboat policy" will not only seriously jeopardize
world peace and development, but will also directly undermine or
even reverse international arms control and disarmament process,
Chinese Ambassador to the Conference on Disarmament (CD) Li
Changhe said here on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The wanton bombing of Yugoslavia by U.S. led-NATO is an "
outright military intervention against a sovereign state", said Li
at a CD plenary session.
</P>
<P>
"It not only undermines the peace in the Balkans but also
upsets the tranquillity of the world," Li said. "They even bombed
the Chinese Embassy in Belgrade, grossly violating international
law and the norms governing international relations."
</P>
<P>
NATO, a typical product of the Cold War, did not disappear from
the world scene with the end of the Cold War, but has been further
expanded, Li said.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, while carrying on the air strikes against Yugoslavia,
this bloc declared its "New Strategic Concept", thus transforming
itself from a defensive military organization to a military one of
offensive nature which can extend its military operation to areas
beyond its borders and use military force against any country
without the United Nations authorization.
</P>
<P>
"If such perverse acts are to continue, the international
community would witness repetitions of similar military
interventions and attacks against those countries which firmly
safeguard their sovereignty and oppose hegemonism and power
politics," Li pointed out.
</P>
<P>
"Under such circumstances when countries which are outside
military alliance would be deprived of basic security, how could
we anticipate any progress in the field of arms control and
disarmament?" Li asked. "Should those small and weak countries be
pushed to the corner, how could they be convinced to support the
international non-proliferation regimes?"
</P>
<P>
Chinese President Jiang Zemin pointed out when he spoke at the
CD session on March 26,that the aim of disarmament is to increase
security.
</P>
<P>
Li quoted Jiang as saying, "Disarmament should not become a
tool for stronger nations to control weaker ones, still less
should it be an instrument for a handful of countries to optimize
their armament in order to seek unilateral security superiority."
</P>
<P>
"China has all along held the view that only just, reasonable
and balanced international arms control and disarmament can
genuinely promote global peace, security and stability," Li told
the CD session.
</P>
<P>
In his statement, Li also reaffirmed China's support for a call
by many CD members that CD should re-establish the Ad Hoc
Committee on the Prevention of an Arms Race in Outer Space.
</P>
<P>
"Progress in this area, just like the progress in working
mechanism on nuclear disarmament, will be conducive to making
progress in formulating the CD's integrated work program
acceptable to all," Li said. "It is the sincere hope of the
Chinese delegation that a favorable turn can come about during the
remaining weeks of the 1999 session." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
