<HEADLINE> Ugandan Top Police Officer Accused of Embezzlement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, May 27 (Xinhua) -- A top Ugandan police officer on
forced leave has been accused of diverting police welfare money to
do his own business.
</P>
<P>
Chris Bakiza, director of the country's Criminal Investigation
Department (CID), is said to have diverted the money to his
company which supplies ceremonial uniforms to the force, the New
Vision daily reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The company, Brevans Enterprises Limited, is run by his wife,
daughter and son, the report added.
</P>
<P>
A witness was quoted as saying that Bakiza had threatened him
with death when he demanded that Bakiza pay back the 19 million
shillings (150,000 U.S. dollars) he lent him to replace the
diverted fund.
</P>
<P>
It was the officer's wife who came to borrow the money because
the officer himself did not want his movements to be monitored by
auditors monitoring him.
</P>
<P>
Bakiza is the second senior police officer charged with using
the force' s money to make personal profits.
</P>
<P>
Former police boss John Odomel faced the same charges last year
and was forced to resign on January 1 this year.
</P>
<P>
The three-man inquiry team responsible for the probe into
Bakiza's case has just been formed by the Ministry of Internal
Affairs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
