<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaria Kills 104 People in Southwestern Kenya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, May 27 (Xinhua) -- About 104 people were killed and at
least 2, 000 hospitalized following an outbreak of malaria in
Kisii District, Nyanza Province, Southwestern Kenya.
</P>
<P>
There are more than 3,100 people have been treated for the
fever and discharged since the outbreak began three weeks ago,
Daily Nation newspaper reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Local doctors fear death toll could be even higher because
there may be more victims died at home without.
</P>
<P>
Patients' relatives have blamed many deaths on the poor state
of roads destroyed by heavy rains and their inability to transport
victims for proper medical care.
</P>
<P>
Doctors said there was an acute congestion of patients at Kisii
District Hospital which has 242 beds and 565 patients.
</P>
<P>
They said that there were adequate supply of malaria drugs in
the district hospital, but lack of intravenous fluids.
</P>
<P>
According to the 1999 World Health Report released by the World
Health Organization, malaria is a leading killer in Africa. The
disease is said to directly or indirectly kill one out of every
four children in sub-sahara Africa. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
