<DOCNO> XIE19990527.0185 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Export Drive Killing Uganda's Fish Industry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, May 27 (Xinhua) -- Uganda's massive catches of the
Nile perch to meet the demand of the export processing factories
is killing the local fishing industry on Lake Victoria, a global
conservation agency has warned.
</P>
<P>
In its recent documentary entitled "Big Fish, Small Fry," the
World Conservation Union said that nearly all the Nile perch
caught goes to the processing factories and on to Europe, Japan
and the United States, the New Vision daily reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The agency warned that the local lakeside fish processing
industry has collapsed and there are almost no Nile perch for sale
on the local markets on the shores of the lake.
</P>
<P>
It said as thousands of people, especially women, are employed
in the marketing and processing of fish, many families have lost a
major source of income due to the massive fishing.
</P>
<P>
The Nile perch export has not only caused the loss of jobs and
livelihoods, but is also responsible for high levels of
malnutrition, especially among children, the agency further
warned.
</P>
<P>
Many local fish mongers along the shores have been forced to
sell the skeletons from the factories as protein source, which
have come to be ironically referred to as "fillet" in Uganda,
according to the findings of the agency.
</P>
<P>
Unless checked, the massive fishing would result in serious
protein shortage and economic problems. Fish export is one of
Uganda's key foreign exchange earners. The east African country
gets over 1.5 billion shillings (1.1 million U.S. dollars) a week
from fish exports. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
