<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tibetan Team Scales Mt. Qomolangma for Ethnic Games Flame </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LHASA, May 27 (Xinhua) -- A 10-strong Tibetan team early on
Thursday successfully scaled Mount Qomolangma, the world's highest
peak, in an unprecedented bid to gather the flame for a national
ethnic Games.
</P>
<P>
The flame, which is to be used at the Sixth Chinese National
Minorities' Games in Lhasa this August, was lit on the 8848-meter
summit with the help of a hot Tibetan sun.
</P>
<P>
The team launched the ascent at 3:00 a.m. from a 8300 meters
camp, and Benba Zaxi became the fastest Chinese conqueror on
Qomolangma when he set foot on the peak at 8:02 a.m. after four
hours and 47 minutes.
</P>
<P>
The other climbers, including Cering Doje, Rigna, Loze, Akabo,
Gambo, Lhaba, Zaxi Gering and women adventurers Gusang and Gigi,
also reached the summit in the span of one hour, quickest time
ever recorded for a climbing team.
</P>
<P>
Gusang became the first Chinese women to conquer Mt. Qunolangma
twice and Rigna and Gigi the first Chinese couple ever to reach
the peak, according to the team captain Samzu.
</P>
<P>
Today's feat also made Benba Zaxi the joint record holder with
Cering Doje and Rigna for the most successful climber in China
with ten above-8000 meters mountains conquered. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
