<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 1 Million Australian Households With Internet Access </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, May 27 (Xinhua) -- The number of Australian
households with Internet access nearly quadrupled in the past two
years to top one million, a survey revealed Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Almost 1.1 million households, nearly 16 percent of the total,
in Australia, had Internet access in 1998 - up from 286,000 in
1996, the Australian Bureau of Statistics (ABS) said.
</P>
<P>
Households with children were the most likely to have access to
the Internet, along with families earning more than 66,000
Australian dollars (43,560 U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
In 1998, 45 percent of Australian homes had a computer and
nearly 16 percent had access to the Internet.
</P>
<P>
Just over 60 percent of Australia's adult population (8.1
million) used a computer and 32 percent (4.2 million) accessed the
Internet in 1998 - mostly from work or home.
</P>
<P>
By international standards, the monthly Internet access cost in
Australia is relative low, totaling 26 U.S. dollars on average per
household user, or about one percent of the per-capita monthly
income.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
