<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Open Wider to Outside World: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, May 27 (Xinhua) -- A senior Chinese official has
declared that China will open wider to the outside world and make
better utilization of overseas investments with the advent of a
new century.
</P>
<P>
Wu Yi, alternate member of the Political Bureau of the Central
Committee of the Communist Party of China (CPC) and a state
councilor, made the remarks on Wednesday at a national conference
on foreign investment utilization in national economic and
technical development zones, which was convened here between May
24 and 26.
</P>
<P>
Wu told foreign investors and local trade officials in east
China's Zhejiang Province and Shanghai during her inspection there
that China's national policy of reform and opening to the outside
world will not change whatever the circumstances.
</P>
<P>
"With the social and economic development of the country, China
will open wider to the outside world in more fields," she stressed.
</P>
<P>
She urged China's 32 national development zones to strive to
refine their investment environment so as to make better use of
overseas investment.
</P>
<P>
The state councilor noted that China remains a favorable
destination for overseas investors because of its political and
social stability, the improvement of the legal environment, its
sustained, fast and sound economic growth, and broad market
potential and relatively cheaper labor.
</P>
<P>
"It will be wise of overseas investors to increase their
investments in China," Wu remarked.
</P>
<P>
She urged local trade officials in charge of national
development zones to sum up the experiences of development zone
operation over the past 20 years and continue to improve the
investment environment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
