<DOCNO> XIE19990527.0198 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysian Business Leader Calls for Fresh ASEAN Capital Flow </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, May 27 (Xinhua) -- Malaysian business leader Ajit Singh
has called for making use of ASEAN attractiveness to draw fresh
foreign direct investment (FDI) flows into the region of the
Association of Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN).
</P>
<P>
"We have to make ASEAN truly borderless so that investment,
goods and services can flow freely across the region," said Ajit
Singh, director of Petronas of Malaysia.
</P>
<P>
In his keynote address at the opening session of a two-day
business forum of ASEAN Chambers of Commerce and Industry, which
began here Wednesday, Singh said ASEAN has the market of half a
billion people and offers the potential investors good terms and
conditions.
</P>
<P>
In the subcontinent, in Africa and in Latin America, free trade
areas are being pushed with added vigor and determination, noted
Singh, who was also former ASEAN Secretary General, adding that
nearly all of these free trade areas started after ASEAN's AFTA
(ASEAN free trade area).
</P>
<P>
He stressed the need to keep ahead of the race by ensuring that
AFTA stays on course and is completed even before its deadline of
2003, calling for new members such as Vietnam, Laos, Myanmar and
Cambodia to make special efforts to join in and not wait until
2006 or 2008.
</P>
<P>
He recalled that between 1990 and 1995, FDI into ASEAN averaged
14.9 billion U.S. dollars annually, saying that in 1996, it
increased to 28.96 billion dollars, representing about 22.45
percent of all FDI flows into developing countries, among which
only China attracted more FDI than ASEAN.
</P>
<P>
In pre-1997, ASEAN had become the fourth largest trading entity
in the world and a major recipient of FDI flows among the
developing countries, he added.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that no one has been immune from the Asian
financial crisis which has prolonged since its outbreak in July
1997, and that all of ASEAN nations have been affected to a larger
or lesser degree.
</P>
<P>
He emphasized the need for ASEAN to become team players instead
of going it alone and trying to beggar-thy-neighbor in the
process.
</P>
<P>
The ASEAN summit in Hanoi, Vietnam, called for the speedier
implementation of AFTA and ASEAN Investment Area and granted
special privileges to ASEAN and non-ASEAN investors investing in
the manufacturing sector between 1999 and 2000 with greater trade
facilitation measures already put in place. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
