<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indian Air Force Launches Third Attacks in Kargil </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, May 27 (Xinhua) -- India Thursday launched its third
air strikes in the Kargil sector of Jammu and Kashmir to help
ground forces to thrash out Pakistan-backed infiltrators, official
sources said here.
</P>
<P>
Indian Air Force (IAF) Wednesday carried out two air strikes in
the above-mentioned area, the first air strikes since 1971 when
India and Pakistan went to war.
</P>
<P>
Thursday's attacks focused on "hideouts and logistic stores of
heavily armed Pakistan-backed infiltrators" in high mountainous
ridges.
</P>
<P>
"The strikes have been successful and effective. The targets
consisted of tented accommodation, logistic stores and hideouts of
the infiltrators. All our combat aircraft have returned safely and
without any damage whatsoever," air force and army officials told
newsmen at a special briefing here.
</P>
<P>
IAF in its strikes used Mig-21, Mig-23, Mig-27 and Mirage-2000
combat jets and sophisticated rockets to pulverize the targets at
heights between 16,000 and 18,000 feet in Drass, Kargil and
Batalic sectors of the Kashmir area, defense sources said here.
</P>
<P>
The air strikes would continue. Infiltrators have suffered
"heavy losses", the sources said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
