<HEADLINE> Several Thousand Filipinos Rally Against VFA </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, May 27 (Xinhua) -- Several thousand Filipinos rallied
Thursday in front of the Philippine Senate to protest against the
ratification of the Visiting Forces Agreement (VFA) as the
senators are scheduled to cast their final votes on the disputed
pact.
</P>
<P>
Anti-VFA groups held a vigil in front of the Senate. A group of
running priests with a giant streamers against the VFA held a
brief demonstration in front of the U.S. embassy early Thursday
morning and ran later to the Senate building to join other
protesters.
</P>
<P>
A group of women installed an altar with the image of Virgin
Mary and held a mass in front of the U.S. embassy after setting
American flags on fire.
</P>
<P>
Soldiers and policemen have secured the senate premises while
lawmen have been dispatched to specific assignments today.
</P>
<P>
The VFA, which was signed by Philippines and U.S. officials
last year, would allow the U.S. to resume major ship visits and
large-scale joint war exercises in the Philippines which were
suspended in 1996.
</P>
<P>
In recent weeks, protesters have held almost daily
demonstrations at the Philippine Senate and the U.S. embassy.
</P>
<P>
Critics say the pact would limit the Philippine government's
right to prosecute American soldiers who commit crimes in the
country, promote prostitution, and drag the Philippines into
conflicts with the United States' enemies. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
