<DOCNO> XIE19990527.0207 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zambia to Rehabilitate Power Facility </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, May 27 (Xinhua) -- Zambia has started a
213-million-U.S. dollar power rehabilitation project to improve
its power generation and distribution, the Zambia Daily Mail
newspaper reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The four-year project is expected to revamp generation at the
Kafue Gorge and Kariba hydro power stations, and improve power
transmission across the country, board chairman of the Zambia
Electricity Supply Corporation, Patrick Nkanza, was quoted as
saying.
</P>
<P>
Nkanza said that with the impending competition in the energy
sector due to the participation of the private, the project will
help improve the reliability of his corporation as a utility
company.
</P>
<P>
The board, management and work force of the electricity supply
corporation are ready for the impending privatization of the
company, he said.
</P>
<P>
The sole power company in the southern African country is
currently involved with both hydro and thermal power generation
and manages transmission lines and distributes power across the
country.
</P>
<P>
Most of the power consumed in Zambia has been generated by the
hydro stations. The 213 million dollars has been provided by the
World Bank. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
