<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0800 GMT, May 27 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
STOCKHOLM -- U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan and Russian
Foreign Minister Igor Ivanov met here Wednesday to discuss the
Kosovo crisis, with neither side releasing any new information
that might be considered special after their talks.
</P>
<P>
Annan said at a news briefing that they focused on "What the
next step will be once we have a breakthrough." He said the United
Nations will be able to play a pivotal role once an agreement on
the peaceful solution to the Kosovo crisis is reached. Ivanov
reiterated Russia's stand on the issue, claiming that NATO has
violated international law in its air raids against Yugoslavia and
must end the attacks. (Russia-UN-Kosovo)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BERLIN -- German Defense Minister Rudolf Scharping said
Wednesday that NATO should maintain heavy military pressure on
Belgrade while continue to seek a political solution to the Kosovo
crisis.
</P>
<P>
Scharping, who had a day-long meeting with his French
counterpart Alai Richard and Polish counterpart Janusz
Onyszkiewicz in Rheinland-Pfalz state Wednesday, said only through
maintaining military pressure can a permanent solution be achieved.
However, he believed NATO should also continue to seek a political
solution and offer humanitarian aid to Kosovo refugees. The most
important objective is to achieve NATO's goals, Scharping said. (
Germany-Meeting-Kosovo)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
SEOUL -- South Korean President Kim Dae-jung left here Thursday
morning on official visits to Russia and Mongolia in a move to
further expand relations with the two countries.
</P>
<P>
President Kim is expected to meet Russian and Mongolian leaders
to discuss economic cooperation and regional security. The South
Korean president is scheduled to meet his Russian counterpart
Boris Yeltsin to secure Russia's support for a peace initiative on
the Korean Peninsula. (SKorea-Russia-Visit) 
</P>
</TEXT>
