<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shanghai To Ban Straw Burning in Fields </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, May 27 (Xinhua) -- Over the next five years China's
industrial and commercial center Shanghai will try to eliminate
pollution resulting from straw burning by making more use of the
material which is a by-product of various crops.
</P>
<P>
Sources with the Shanghai Municipal Agricultural Commission say
the rural areas of the city produce about three million tons of
straw annually.
</P>
<P>
As fewer farmers use it for lighting fires or as manure, the
greater part of the straw is usually burned in the fields, which
constitutes a major source of pollution while also wasting
potential resources.
</P>
<P>
From this summer the burning of straw will be banned and a
number of factories will be set up to make manure and building
materials out of the product.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai's ban on straw burning is only part of China's effort
to do away with related pollution nationwide.
</P>
<P>
In a recent joint effort, six Chinese ministerial departments
have prohibited straw burning along major roads and around
airports to protect the environment and promote safety.
</P>
<P>
People who do so and cause serious air pollution will be
subject to fines, according to a regulation jointly issued by the
State Environmental Protection Administration, the ministries of
agriculture, finance, railways and communications, and the General
Administration of Civil Aviation.
</P>
<P>
China produces more than 600 million tons of crop straw each
year and farmers, especially in economically developed regions
like Shanghai, usually burn it whenever and wherever they like.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990527.0223 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Trains to Run Faster </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, May 27 (Xinhua) -- The speed of trains on the railway
between Hangzhou, capital of east China's Zhejiang Province, and
Zhuzhou, a major city in central China's Hunan Province, will be
increased to 120 km per hour from the present 90 km per hour as of
October 1.
</P>
<P>
The program is part of China's massive efforts to raise the
speed of trains across the country to meet the needs of the
national economy and to sharpen the competitive edge of railways
on the whole transport market.
</P>
<P>
Railway transport in China has been challenged by express
highways and civil aviation in recent years. Statistics show that
train transport volume accounted for only 38.8 percent of the
country's total transportation volume in 1998, compared with 60.5
percent in 1980.
</P>
<P>
China began to improve train speeds on April 1, 1997, and the
average travel speed of the country's trains has since increased
to 54.9 from 48.1 km per hour. On the three major lines from
Beijing to Guangzhou, Shanghai and Harbin, trains now run at 140
km per hour.
</P>
<P>
Sources with the Ministry of Railways say China is now
considering building a high-speed railway linking its capital with
its largest industrial center, Shanghai, in the year 2000, with a
total length of 1,300 km at a designed speed of more than 250 km
per hour.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
