<HEADLINE> China Witnesses Booming of Book Sales </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 27 (Xinhua) -- China has witnessed a booming of
book sales with the residents' annual expenditure on books
exceeding that on tobacco for the first time.
</P>
<P>
According to today's Guangming Daily, Beijing residents'
expenditure on books ranks top among the country's other provinces,
municipalities and autonomous regions.
</P>
<P>
A sample survey on 110 Beijing book stores in eight urban
districts indicated that half the urban residents spend 100 (12 U.
S. dollars) to 500 yuan (60 dollars) a year on buying books while
the country's average number stands at 25 yuan (three dollars).
</P>
<P>
Beijing Book Building, the largest state-owned book retailer,
has sold out more than five million copies of books since its
opening last May with sales volume of over 100 million yuan (12
million dollars).
</P>
<P>
The daily reported that around 30,000 people, including
overseas customers, visit the book building each day and the
number would be doubled at weekends.
</P>
<P>
Among the 500 interviewees of the sample survey, 297 people
choose book stores with more varieties of books and 171 say they
would go to book stores nearby.
</P>
<P>
Beijing Book Building, with a 52,000-square-meter flood space,
has established business relations with over 500 publishing houses
in the country and is providing over 160,000 kinds of books.
</P>
</TEXT>
