<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Imports From Russia Surge in First 4 Months </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 27 (Xinhua) -- China's imports from Russia surged
a record 42 percent in the first four months of the year, hitting
1.374 billion U.S. dollars, according to latest statistics from
the General Administration of Customs.
</P>
<P>
Total bilateral trade volume between China and Russia grew 1.7
percent in the period, reaching 1.710 billion U.S. dollars.
Meanwhile, China's exports to Russia plummeted 53 percent compared
with the corresponding period last year.
</P>
<P>
The increase of imports from Russia was mainly because of a
surge in imports of timber, rolled steel, chemical materials,
aluminum, machinery and electronic products, according to the
Ministry of Foreign Trade and Economic Cooperation (MOFTEC).
</P>
<P>
A trade expert here told Xinhua that the increase of imports
from Russia was due to China's policy of stimulating domestic
demand and the policy to encourage imports since early this year.
</P>
<P>
"The growth of imports from Russia is likely to continue in the
coming several months but the growth rate might slow down," he
said. "As China's imports increased sharply in the first few
months of the year, the market demand for raw materials will be
smaller. In addition, Russia has started to increase export tax,
which will also increase costs for Chinese importers."
</P>
<P>
He attributed the nose-dive of exports to Russia to the
sluggish market demand in that country. Russia's tightened control
of foreign exchange was another factor that led to the decline.
</P>
<P>
In addition, he said the norms of trade between China and
Russia need to be refined and China needs to improve the
competitiveness of its export products as well.
</P>
<P>
However, China's exports to Russia in April grew to about the
same level of the corresponding period last year, he noted.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
