<HEADLINE> Foreign Investors Still Enthusiastic of Cooperating With China (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 27 (Xinhua) -- Western investors, including those
from the United States, are still enthusiastic about cooperating
closely with China despite the country's severe criticism of the U.
S.-led NATO's attack on the Chinese Embassy in Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
The Shenzhen Sino-American OCT International Trading Company
Ltd., the first Sino-American foreign trade company that began
operations on May 25, was considered by analysts as proof that the
Chinese market is still attractive.
</P>
<P>
On May 19, business leaders and representatives of 17
influential companies or institutions accepted letters of
invitation from Beijing Mayor Liu Qi to act as his first group of
economic advisors.
</P>
<P>
In a recent speech, Chinese President Jiang Zemin pledged that
China will unswervingly carry out its reform and open-up drive to
help the country become stronger.
</P>
<P>
Increased calls at Chinese ports by foreign vessels and the
growing numbers of overseas tourists visiting China's cities,
coupled with news reports saying foreigners in China are doing
well, has all contributed to the feeling of ongoing good will.
</P>
<P>
At the Tianjin Port's bonded zone one official said, "China's
door has remained open to the outside world."
</P>
<P>
Gary Tooker, Chairman of Motorola Inc. of the United States,
said during a recent business trip to Tianjin that his company
would not change its plan of adding a further 1.5 billion U.S.
dollars of investment to its China operations. The plan was
announced by the company before U.S. President Bill Clinton made
an official visit to China last June. Motorola Company is now the
largest U.S. investor in China.
</P>
<P>
Sven-Christer Nilsson, CEO and President of Ericsson, pledged
in Beijing on May 20 that his company's investment in China would
climb to 600 million U.S. dollars by next year.
</P>
<P>
"As long as China pushes forward its open-up drive, then there
will be no interruption in the flow of direct foreign investment
into the country," said Tasuku Takagaki, Chairman of the Tokyo-
Mitsubishi Bank, last week.
</P>
<P>
Kvaerner, a British company specializing in engineering and
construction, has completed more than 350 projects in China since
1978. It is now building a further 80 projects in China.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
