<HEADLINE> Foreign Investors Still Enthusiastic of Cooperating With China (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
In the view of foreign investors China has considerable long
term attractions and advantages such as a favorable economic and
political environment and huge internal market potential.
</P>
<P>
The Hoechst Company of Germany claimed in a report issued last
week that Beijing, Shanghai and Hong Kong will continue to be the
most attractive investment destinations in the fast shifting east.
</P>
<P>
By late 1999, Shanghai alone will pump in investments of 40
billion U.S. dollars into fixed assets and infrastructure, one
third of which will be covered by overseas partners.
</P>
<P>
U.S. automaker Ford Motor Company last week published a
forecast bulletin in which it said China's auto industry will
become one of the world's largest in the next century, with
annual sales amounting to four million cars by 2010, and therefore,
it will continue to cooperate with China in developing environment-
friendly vehicles.
</P>
<P>
Many foreign investors said the cooperative attitude of the
government towards improving the transparency of work,
infrastructure and related services are the most important factors
for them to choose investment destinations.
</P>
<P>
So far, China has become the world's second largest country in
terms of the volume of overseas investment. By late 1998, some 324,
000 overseas-backed enterprises had emerged in China, with
investment exceeding 267.4 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Analysts generally believe that China's efforts to gain
accession to the World Trade Organization, including opening up
such fields as commerce, foreign trade and air transport to
foreign investors, will make it even more attractive to investors.
</P>
</TEXT>
