<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Africans Abroad Go to Polls </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, May 26 (Xinhua) -- South Africa's second
democratic election got underway Wednesday as South Africans
working and studying abroad cast special votes at the country's
foreign missions.
</P>
<P>
However, in terms of electoral regulations, South African
holiday makers, tourists and cricket fans in Europe for the
Cricket World Cup were excluded from casting their ballots.
</P>
<P>
Back home, security personnel on election duty on June 2,
Independent Electoral Commission (IEC) officials, and voters who
will be abroad on the voting day, were also able to cast their
ballots.
</P>
<P>
The polling station at the High Commission in the Australian
capital Canberra was the first to open but officials said only 16
people -- five of them high commission staff -- had voted by 8
p.m. local time, an hour before polling closed, South African
Press Association (SAPA) reported.
</P>
<P>
The embassy in Beijing, home to a permanent community of only
40 South Africans, saw around a dozen voters by late afternoon,
according to first secretary Izak Human.
</P>
<P>
More than 70 South Africans -- many of them cricket fans on
their way to the World Cup match between South Africa and Kenya in
Amsterdam -- had voted at the embassy in The Hague in The
Netherlands by noon.
</P>
<P>
In London, a small but steady trickle of voters passed through
the halls of South Africa House to cast their ballots, according
to SAPA.
</P>
<P>
The scene was in stark contrast to five years ago when election
officials had their hands full coping with a queue of eager, many
first- time, voters.
</P>
<P>
Once the polling stations closed at 9 p.m., the ballot boxes
would be emptied and the votes placed into special bags and sealed
before being transported back to South Africa.
</P>
<P>
All foreign votes will be counted at a polling station in
central Pretoria, IEC spokeswoman Lydia Young said.
</P>
<P>
Polling stations at the South African embassy in Washington and
the consulate in New York reported a slow start but expected the
pace to pick up around lunch time.
</P>
<P>
The voting at home and abroad was rather smooth with only small
hitches.
</P>
<P>
In Gauteng Province, the presiding officer at the Winchester
Ridge Primary School south of Johannesburg, Liam Clarke, was
hijacked while unloading ballot papers at the school when a gunman
ordered him to hand over his vehicle's keys, SAPA said.
</P>
<P>
Police managed to recover the IEC vehicle, including national
and provincial ballot papers and security stamps, although
declaration certificates, which looked like cheques, were not
recovered.
</P>
<P>
IEC officials said they believed the incident was not
politically motivated.
</P>
<P>
Another IEC vehicle was stolen in the Johannesburg South Area
Wednesday, while two rented vehicles were hijacked on the West
Rand Tuesday. One council vehicle used for electoral purposes was
stolen last week.
</P>
<P>
Wednesday's special voting day was specifically for security
force members, but instead IEC officials allowed people like
journalists and pensioners, who were supposed to make arrangements
to vote next week, to cast their votes Wednesday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
