<DOCNO> XIE19990527.0238 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Zealand's Imports Keep Rising </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, May 27 (Xinhua) -- New Zealand's imports have been
rising each month over the past two years, while its exports trend
 flattening in contrast to the rise in imports, pushing the annual
trade deficit to record levels.
</P>
<P>
In a media release, Statistics NZ said Thursday that
provisional merchandise imports for April 1999 were 2.02 billion
NZ dollars (1.1 billion U.S. dollars), 8.2 percent higher than in
the same month of the previous year.
</P>
<P>
Preliminary estimates of New Zealand's exports for April show
an expected trade deficit of 55 million NZ dollars (30 million
U.S. dollars) for the month and 1.32 billion NZ dollars (726
million U.S. dollars) for the year ending April 1999.
</P>
<P>
During the 1990s, the average trade balance of the country for
the month of April, including April 1999, was a surplus of 175
million NZ dollars (96 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
The release cited imports of cars and household goods as major
contributors to the overall import growth.
</P>
<P>
After a quiet period from late 1997 to early 1998, imports of
cars have risen strongly and returned to the level of two years
ago.
</P>
<P>
"The removal of tariffs on imported cars in May 1998 and the
closure of the New Zealand car assembly industry have played a
part in this growth," New Zealand Acting Government Statistician
Dianne Macaskill said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
