<HEADLINE> UK Tightens Sanctions on UNITA </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, May 26 (Xinhua) -- British Ambassador to Angola
Caroline Helmes Wednesday reiterated that her government is to
tighten its sanctions on the National Union for the Total
Independence of Angola (UNITA), in accordance with the U.N.
resolutions.
</P>
<P>
Helmes emphasized that Britain will, together with other U.N.
members, try to make the U.N. sanctions on UNITA more effective,
thus forcing UNITA leader Jonas Savimbi to giver up his war
policy.
</P>
<P>
"Britain supports U.N. stand on the Angola issue and feel sad
over the renewed war in Angola," the ambassador said, adding that
Savimbi should be held responsible for the civil war in the
country, as he has violated the Lusaka Peace Protocol signed in
1994.
</P>
<P>
She said she wishes Angola would achieve peace in the country,
as it is very important to the development in southern Africa,
where Britain has extensive political, diplomatic and economic
interests.
</P>
<P>
The Angolan government, in a recent diplomatic offensive, has
demanded the international community strictly observe the U.N.
resolutions on Angola, which include the sanctions on UNITA's
import of oil and arms, and the ban on UNITA leaders trips abroad,
the closure of UNITA offices overseas and its export of diamond.
</P>
<P>
The Angolan government has been accusing some European and
African countries, including British companies, of continuing
their secret support to the UNITA, for which the U.N. Security
Council has decided this month to investigate.  
</P>
</TEXT>
