<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> E. African States to Jointly Combat Y2k Problem </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, May 26 (Xinhua) -- East African countries have
drawn up plans to jointly combat the looming computer Year 2000
(Y2K) problem.
</P>
<P>
The Chairman of Tanzania's National Y2k Advisory Team, David
Sawe, said here Wednesday that a number of resolutions have been
adopted at a meeting by heads of the region's Y2k campaign.
</P>
<P>
He said sharing and development of common information sources
and the exchange of best practice standards were agreed during the
conference held this week in Arusha, north Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
Sawe, who represented Tanzania at the meeting, said that an
action plan has been worked out for skills development and
long-term capacity building.
</P>
<P>
The conference was part of East Africa Cooperation (EAC)'s
initiative to coordinate in solving the Y2k problem.
</P>
<P>
Delegates to the meeting made a statement, saying people have
the right to expect that everything possible is done to minimize
risks of their well being and daily life, Sawe said.
</P>
<P>
A joint communique of the delegates stated that individuals and
organizations within the region are required, as a matter of
urgency, to improve their awareness of the Y2k problem, assess
likely impact on the operating environments, implement remediation
and contingency plans, and ensure that adequate testing and
verification is done.
</P>
<P>
The conference also adopted terms of reference for regional
cooperation among the national Y2k task forces and for the
regional liaison working group on electricity and petrochemical
sectors.
</P>
<P>
The delegates said that east Africa has a role to play in
spearheading a war against the Y2K problem in the continent, Sawe
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990527.0247 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bangladesh Holds Meeting on Parliamentary Committee System </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, May 27 (Xinhua) -- A conference on parliamentary
committee systems, organized by the Institute of Parliamentary
Studies of the Bangladesh Parliament, started here Thursday
morning.
</P>
<P>
The two-day conference, focusing on issues related to the
parliamentary committee system in Bangladesh, will cover such
issues as oversight of the government, the role of women within
the committees, the role of the committee chairpersons, and the
role of the committees in budget procedures.
</P>
<P>
"The social system of Bangladesh has provisions for rule of
law, parliamentary democracy and accountable government," said
Prime Minister Sheikh Hasina, who is also leader of parliament,
while inaugurating the conference.
</P>
<P>
The closing ceremony will be addressed by Khaleda Zia, leader
of the opposition in parliament.
</P>
<P>
"Committees are essential tools" which "provide a forum where
debates can take place on the basis of rationale rather than
passion... with less space for demagogy... more chances for
reaching consensus," Hasina said.
</P>
<P>
She said that a number of improvements were initiated in recent
years through amendments to the Rules of Procedure, such as
reconstituting the standing committees on ministries to make
non-minister members of parliament to head the committees,
introducing prime minister's question time to make the executive
branch of government more accountable to parliament, and deciding
to refer all bills introduced in the parliament by the government
to standing committees for examination and scrutinization before
enactment.
</P>
<P>
"Parliament is the center of all activities. We believe all
national problems could be solved through discussion in the
parliament," she said.
</P>
<P>
Speakers from India and Britain will present papers at the
conference about the committee systems of parliament in their
respective countries, and an international parliamentary expert
from the United Nations Development Program will deliver a speech
on the comparative constitutional law.
</P>
<P>
Some 400 people, including ministers and members of parliament,
are participating in the conference, which is targeted at members
and senior officials of the Secretariat of the Bangladesh
Parliament. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
