<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesian Badminton Rues Copenhagen Debacle </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, May 27 (Xinhua) -- Indonesian disappointment at the
Sudirman Cup and the World Championships in Denmark last week has
left with it a warning that the country's badminton is facing the
prospect of being potential "pushovers" in the world scene.
</P>
<P>
"Other countries appeared to have improved a step ahead of us,"
said Christian Hadinata, chief of the Indonesian Badminton
Federation (PBSI) in charge of the training center program.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia, which were deprived of the country's number one
female player Mia Audina, were beaten by Denmark in the semifinals
of the Sudirman Cup and neither player was able to get into the
semifinals of the World Championships.
</P>
<P>
"A few months ago, our men's doubles were still able to win,
but now we seem to be powerless. Our men's singles can still
maintain the balance with the world, but we are painfully lagging
behind in the women's singles," Christian was quoted by The
Indonesian Observer Thursday as saying.
</P>
<P>
He said PBSI must pick up the pace to come up with the
achievement made by other countries' players by seeking remedies
to weaknesses.
</P>
<P>
"Coaching must be intensely heeded. We'll call in experts in
skills-upgrading, psychologists and body trainers. In short we
shall adopt technology and science," Christian said.
</P>
<P>
He was opposed to a suggestion that some of the coaches at the
training center be replaced. He agreed, though, they should
upgrade their coaching skills.
</P>
<P>
"Don't be short-sighted in viewing the matter. They may have
failed in Denmark, but they still deserve praise for what they did
in the previous events such as in the Asian Games and All England.
The existing coaches can still be relied on. Don't rush ourselves
to a hasty judgement. What is left to do is evaluation," he added.
</P>
<P>
Referring specifically to the Copenhagen disaster, Christian
admitted to having slipped up and was likely to have applied the
wrong strategy.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, former world champion Icuk Sugiarto voiced criticism
that the PBSI training program had looked like going nowhere while
rivalry has now become stiff.
</P>
<P>
"Foreign line-ups are now the names to beat and this needs
research and should give us motivation," said Icuk, who won the
men's singles trophy in 1983.
</P>
<P>
He questioned the loose monitoring of the coaches by the
federation, saying that the players -- now at the training center -
- are no longer national class but are already world class, which
subsequently needs good quality mentors. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
