<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bangladesh Okays Proposed Annual Development Program </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, May 27 (Xinhua) -- The Bangladeshi government has
approved a 155 billion taka (3.2 billion U.S. dollars) annual
development program (ADP) for July 1999-June 2000 fiscal year to
further spur the economy, press reports said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
This approval was made at a meeting of the National Economic
Council Wednesday with Prime Minister Sheikh Hasina in the chair.
The size of the revised ADP for the outgoing fiscal year is 140
billion taka (2.89 billion dollars).
</P>
<P>
In the ADP outlay, local currency will amount to 88.3 billion
taka (1.82 billion dollars) or 57 percent of the total, while the
project aid will be 64.26 billion taka (1.32 billion dollars) and
food aid 2.44 billion taka (50.3 million dollars), Press Secretary
to the prime minister Jawadul Karim was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
Nearly 40 percent of the allocations in the new ADP will be for
the social sector, covering rural development, youth and women
development and health and 37 percent for poverty alleviation,
according to State Minister for Planning Mohiuddin Khan Alamgir.
</P>
<P>
The total number of ADP projects to be implemented in the
coming fiscal year is 1,293, with the thrust being on poverty
alleviation, spread of education and on power sector.
</P>
<P>
Industry, gas and power, civil aviation, telecommunications,
railway, export processing zones development and other important
sectors have been opened for private investment, and the
government gave special attention to privatization in adopting the
new projects in the ADP.
</P>
<P>
The proposed ADP will be formally announced in the parliament
in June, along with the next national budget. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990527.0259 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Is Biggest Source for HK's Long Term Growth: TDC Chairman </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, May 27 (Xinhua) -- The biggest potential source of
growth for Hong Kong in the longer term is its special connection
to China's mainland, Victor Fung, chairman of the Hong Kong Trade
Development Council (TDC), said here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Delivering the opening remarks for the Financial Conference on
Asia '99, Fung said that China's likely entry into the World Trade
Organization (WTO) by the end of this year is good news for Hong
Kong's business community.
</P>
<P>
Some analysts believe China's accession to the WTO will be the
beginning of the end of Hong Kong's traditional role as gateway to
China.
</P>
<P>
"I believe exactly the opposite," Fung said.
</P>
<P>
China's joining the WTO will mean improved access to mainland
markets, increased trade between China and the developed economies,
increased transparency in trade regulations, closer integration
and co-operation on trade and tariff negotiations, and further
liberalization of the mainland's services sectors.
</P>
<P>
As the premier gateway for trade and investment to and from
China's mainland, anything that increases these flows will help
Hong Kong, Fung said.
</P>
<P>
The argument that more companies will deal directly with
China's mainland is true, but the increase in trade will be so
much, that the entire pie will increase, not just the portion of
trade going directly to the mainland, he added.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong is fast becoming the expertise and funding center for
efforts to modernize the Chinese mainland economy.
</P>
<P>
Enterprises on the mainland need financing and professional
expertise to turn their operations around the modernization, Fung
said. That's where Hong Kong comes in, he added.
</P>
<P>
Enterprises on the mainland continue to come to Hong Kong to
list on the stock exchange and raise money for activities on the
mainland.
</P>
<P>
And more than 100,000 Hong Kong people are working in the
Chinese mainland, many of them in highly-skilled management
positions offering expertise in accounting, project financing,
design, advertising and legal services.
</P>
<P>
Offering expertise and funding for economic restructuring will
be central to the role Hong Kong will play in helping China's
modernization drive, Fung said.
</P>
<P>
Also by being so deeply involved in this effort, Hong Kong will
further integrate with the mainland economy and inevitably be in a
position to influence other major challenges facing China's
mainland, Fung said.
</P>
<P>
This key role in the economic future of China's mainland, plus
Hong Kong's own growing role as an offshore trade hub and a center
for multinational corporations business activity, are three major
areas of growth that help ensure a bright future for Hong Kong,
Fung noted.
</P>
<P>
A number of signs have started appearing on the horizon that
indicate that the economic downturn in Hong Kong may have bottomed
out and that recovery is beginning, Fung said.
</P>
<P>
First of all, the Hang Seng Index has rebounded from a low of
about 6,500 points last August and has effectively doubled in the
last 9 months.
</P>
<P>
Property sales resumed again last month, after a moratorium of
9 months. Initial reaction has been very positive.
</P>
<P>
GDP growth is expected to pick up dramatically towards the end
of the year. The Hong Kong government estimates that GDP growth
for 1999 will be about 0.5 percent, Hongkong Bank is forecasting
about -1 percent, and a recent survey of economists quoted by the
Asian Wall Street Journal has growth at about -1.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
All of these figures mean that during the last quarter and
possibly two quarters, growth will be back in the black and Hong
Kong on its way out of recession, Fung said.
</P>
<P>
Tourism figures are rebounding. About 100,000 more visitors
came to Hong Kong last month than in February.
</P>
<P>
One of the most potent signs of recovery is the results of
recent trade fairs organized by the Hong Kong Trade Development
Council.
</P>
<P>
TDC's last four fairs -- Fashion Week, the Toy Fair, the
Jewelry Fair and at the Gift and Housewares Fair -- all showed a
significant increase in the number of exhibitors and overseas
buyers coming to Hong Kong to do business.
</P>
<P>
On top of all this, in recent polls Hong Kong people have said
they feel much more confident about the economy in 1999 than last
year, Fung said.
</P>
<P>
The two-day conference is organized by the TDC with a theme of
"Asian Finance: Turmoil, Regulations and Recovery." Speakers
include financial and banking officials, specialists, professors
from Hong Kong, China's mainland and other Asian countries.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
