<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: HK's Tourism Industry Moves Towards Recovery </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, May 27 (Xinhua) -- After a year and a half of
recession, Hong Kong's tourism industry, one of the worst sectors
hit by the Asian financial crisis, is beginning to show signs of
recovery.
</P>
<P>
During the first four months of this year, Hong Kong hosted a
total of 3.4 million visitors from all over the world, who were
equivalent to half of its population and represented a 13 percent
increase from the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
The sustained growth of the number of visitors to Hong Kong has
continued for 10 consecutive months since last July, which
contrasted sharply with the severe declines of 11 percent in the
year-on-year number of visitors in 1997 and 8 percent in 1998 due
to the Asian financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, a total of 89 hotels throughout Hong Kong
were busier in the first four months this year than that of last
year with their average room occupancy rate ranging between 74
percent and 81 percent.
</P>
<P>
As Stephen Ip, secretary for Economic Services, has said: "this
is particularly encouraging when most of our major neighboring
competitors are still suffering from a downturn in visitor
arrivals."
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong's tourism industry is one of the important pillars in
its economy. It generated a total of 72.6 billion HK dollars (9.31
billion U.S. dollars) last year in gross business receipts,
contributing 5 percent to GDP.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the tourism industry maintained its role as a
major employer, creating jobs for some 330,000 people, or about 10
percent of the Hong Kong labor force in the year.
</P>
<P>
Analysts attributed the continued recovery in visitor arrivals
and hotel occupancy mainly to the tremendous efforts the
government and all sectors of the tourism industry have made to
keep Hong Kong competitive.
</P>
<P>
The government is pursuing a series of important measures to
strengthen Hong Kong's position as a leading travel and tourist
destination in Asia.
</P>
<P>
It has put in place a three-pronged strategy to sustain the
long-term development of tourism by promoting Hong Kong to
overseas tourists, enhancing its attractiveness as well as
facilitating the entry of visitors into Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
The Hong Kong Tourist Association also gears up its efforts to
highlight the city's diversity and its unique international
metropolis blending East with West by launching various colorful
activities such as a worldwide New Destination Campaign entitled "
We are Hong Kong - City of Life" and a "Discover Hong Kong"
initiative.
</P>
<P>
Besides, Hong Kong's geographical proximity to and its intimate
connection with vast fast developing mainland market add unique
strength to it.
</P>
<P>
The central government reached an agreement with the government
of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region earlier last year
that starting from last July, the quota of mainland visitors to
Hong Kong would rise from 1,142 to 1,500 everyday.
</P>
<P>
The mainland's favorable outbound policies and a shorter visa
processing time keep the steady growth of the number of visitors
to Hong Kong. Only in February this year, travelers from the
mainland to Hong Kong rose by 65.2 percent over the same month
last year.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, Hong Kong has a liberal visa regime which enables
visitors from over 170 countries and regions to enter Hong Kong
visa-free.
</P>
<P>
Continuing economic improvement in some Asian countries such as
Indonesia and south Korea was another factor for increasing number
of arrivals to Hong Kong. Visitors from Indonesia in April this
year rose by 83.4 percent, showing the strongest growth in Asian
markets.
</P>
<P>
How does Hong Kong continue to maintain the momentum of growth
in tourism industry?
</P>
<P>
A grand tourism promotion blueprint has been formulated by the
government, which includes the plans to build up attractions such
as a cable car system on Lantau, an international wetland park
near the world-famous Mai Po Marshes, and a fisherman's wharf in
Aberdeen.
</P>
<P>
It is noticeable that there are the negotiations with Walt
Disney over a possible theme park.
</P>
<P>
Apart from working on improving its hardware, Hong Kong is also
mindful of developing its software, including the promotion of new
tourist products and facilities as well as attractive
international events.
</P>
<P>
About 100 interactive computer information kiosks have been
installed at major tourist spots where tourist information can be
obtained easily.
</P>
<P>
The government has also set up a 100-million-HK-dollar (12.82
million U.S. dollar) International Events Fund to support the
staging of some 50 international events in Hong Kong over the next
five years.
</P>
<P>
It is also planning for a world-class, state-of-the-art new
performance venue at West Kowloon Reclamation.
</P>
<P>
Besides, the government will continue to take measures to
facilitate the immigration clearance of visitors to Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
All of these will surely bring a bright future to Hong Kong's
tourism industry.
</P>
<P>
Local Analysts said with certainty that so long as the
government's plans are implemented step by step, Hong Kong's
travel and tourism industry will continue to revive.
</P>
<P>
They predicted a 3.5 percent growth in visitor arrivals this
year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
