<HEADLINE> Xinhua World Economic News Summary at 0500 GMT, May 27 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- The World Bank approved on Wednesday a total of
250 million U.S. dollars in loans and credits to help China
increase the incomes of poor farmers and agricultural production.
</P>
<P>
The bank's executive board approved a 80-million-dollar loan
and a 20-million-dollar credit for the Guanzhong Irrigation
Improvement Project and a 100-million-dollar loan and a 50-million-
dollar credit for the Second Loess Plateau Watershed
Rehabilitation Project. (WB-China)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- The International Monetary Fund (IMF) approved on
Wednesday a credit totaling 300 million U.S. dollars for Algeria
under the Compensatory and Contingency Financing Facility (CCFF)
to help the African country offset a temporary shortfall in
exports of goods and services.
</P>
<P>
The CCFF aims to assist IMF members experiencing temporary
shortfalls in export earnings. The loans are repayable between 3.
25 and 5 years, and carry a standard annual interest charge, which
is currently 3.52 percent. (IMF-Algeria)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
NEW YORK -- Wall Street stocks rebounded strongly Wednesday as
traders eased their concerns about higher interest rates.
</P>
<P>
The Dow Jones industrial average closed up 171.07 at 10,702.16.
The index lost 356.26 points or 3.2 percent in the past four
sessions.
</P>
<P>
Broader stock indicators were also higher. The Standard &AMP;
Poor's 500 index rose 20.36 at 1,304.76 and the technology heavy
Nasdaq composite index rose 46.28 at 2,427.18. (US-Wall Street-
Stocks)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BUENAS AIRES -- Argentina's Vice Minister of Economy Pablo
Guidotti said on Wednesday that the rumours of a possible
devaluation of the Argentine currency, the peso, "have no
foundation."
</P>
<P>
These rumors have affected the local markets of the country and
the region, and have arisen "for speculative reasons," over the
past few days, he said.
</P>
<P>
"Fortunately, the markets have calmed down in the face of the
evidence that there will not be changes" he said, referring to the
Argentine policy on the free exchange of the peso against the U.S.
dollar, which was initiated on April 1, 1991. (Argentina-Currency)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
PRAGUE -- The number of economic crimes in the Czech Republic
in 1998 hit 36,000 cases, up 5,875 cases or 19.5 percent over 1997,
said a report published by the Czech Ministry of the Interior on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Statistics from a report titled: "Czech National Secure Status
in 1998," showed that financial losses resulting from economic
crimes in 1998 amounted to 21 billion koruna (600 million US.
dollars ), an increase of 21.6 percent over 1997. (Czech Republic-
Economic Crimes) 
</P>
</TEXT>
