<BODY>
<HEADLINE> A Comment on Cox Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 27 (Xinhua) -- The specter of McCarthyism looms
large in the Cox report drawn up by a U.S. House committee led by
Republican Representative Christopher Cox on the so-called China's
"theft" of U.S. nuclear secrets.
</P>
<P>
While alleging China in the past decades has made "widespread
effort to obtain U.S. military technology by any means, legal or
illegal," the report contains no legally tenable evidence but
instead many vague terms such as "may" and "likely" to back up its
accusations.
</P>
<P>
The malign slanders heaped on China and the term of "China
threat" trumpeted by the report have proved nothing other than the
ulterior motives of a handful of U.S. congressmen who, eager in
slinging mud at China, appear to be reliving the witch-hunt years
of the notorious McCarthyism nearly half a century ago.
</P>
<P>
Cox and his like, using the same base and shabby methods as
those used by Joseph McCarthy in the 1950s, have managed to plunge
every overseas Chinese in the United States into a state of
extreme nervousness and insecurity.
</P>
<P>
As is well-known, China's military technologies are the result
of hard work and wisdom of its own scientists and engineers under
the policy of "independence and self-reliance" firmly pursued by
the Chinese government.
</P>
<P>
Long before Beijing and Washington established diplomatic
relations in 1979, China had successfully developed the H-bomb, A-
bomb and satellites. The wisdom of Chinese scientists is self-
evident.
</P>
<P>
The Cox report, in its arrogance to underestimate the wisdom
and creativity of Chinese scientists, constitutes a serious insult
to the Chinese people.
</P>
<P>
China has always abided by the U.N. Charter and the norm
governing international relations and sought for peaceful
coexistence with all countries in the world, including the United
States.
</P>
<P>
China has never engaged in nuclear arms race and has announced
it will never be the first to use nuclear weapons. Its possession
of a limited amount of nuclear weapons is solely meant for self-
defense.
</P>
<P>
From whatever perspective -- technological, moral or political,
China sees no need to "steal" military high-tech, or anything
indeed, from the United States, or any other country.
</P>
<P>
Just as Chinese Prime Minister Zhu Rongji pointed out, "China's
theft" is like a tale of the "Arabian Nights."
</P>
<P>
The cooking-up of Cox's report is no accidental.
</P>
<P>
There are some people in the United States who are always
hostile and prejudiced against China. Disregarding the trend of
history, they would never let go the Cold War mentality.
</P>
<P>
They spread rumors and look every nook and cranny for anything
that might be useful in their fabrication of the "China threat" to
undermine the friendship between the Chinese and U.S. peoples. The
Cox report is just one of the latest examples.
</P>
<P>
Not long ago, the U.S.-led NATO mounted a missile attack on the
Chinese Embassy in Belgrade, which has been condemned in the
strongest term by the Chinese government and people, as well as
the international community.
</P>
<P>
Turning a deaf ear to all calls for a thorough investigation
into the attack, the U.S. Congress, instead, concocted the Cox
report, in a full betrayal of the vicious intentions and political
plot of certain U.S. politicians to fan up anti-China sentiments
and divert attention from the embassy raid.
</P>
<P>
Reflecting on history can bring the present into focus. Just
like the short-lived McCarthyist persecution, the conducts of Cox
and his like, which will undermine the fundamental interests of
the United States and runs counter to the wish of the American
people to develop friendly ties with China, will eventually be
rejected with scorn. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990527.0264 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Myanmar Seeks Ways to Increase Intra-ASEAN Trade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, May 27 (Xinhua) -- Myanmar is exploring ways to
increase intra-ASEAN trade, looking into the use of ASEAN
currencies in conducting trade among ASEAN members as well as for
greater use of products produced locally within the region, said
Myanmar leader Lieutenant-General Khin Nyunt.
</P>
<P>
Khin Nyunt, who is First Secretary of the Myanmar State Peace
and Development Council, made the remarks on Thursday's session of
a two-day business forum of Chambers of Commerce and Industry of
the Association of Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN) which began
here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
No nation in the region has escaped the effects of the economic
and financial crisis which has prolonged for nearly two years, he
said, describing the crisis as "an unprecedented challenge" to the
Southeast Asian region.
</P>
<P>
He said that the signs of recovery have already emerged, saying
that Myanmar is fully confident that the region will regain the
dynamism in the very near future.
</P>
<P>
Dealing with internal issue, Khin Nyunt said with the
introduction of political, economic and administrative reforms
following the taking over of power by the present government in
1988, Myanmar is now on the path to progress and prosperity.
</P>
<P>
"At the moment, the government may be in the form of a military
government, but it is an administration which is laying down the
foundation for the establishment of a democratic system that is in
keeping with the conditions of the country as well as the
aspirations of the entire people," he stated.
</P>
<P>
"Once the constitutional process is concluded, a constitutional
government will lead the nation," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
