<HEADLINE> Myanmar Seizes 1,197 Kilos of Drugs in April </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, May 27 (Xinhua) -- Myanmar seized a total of 1,197
kilos of narcotic drugs including 52.62 kilos of heroin and 239.01
kilos of opium in April, The New Light of Myanmar newspaper
reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Army units, police and the customs also confiscated 4.19 kilos
of marijuana, 43.42 liters of phensedyl and 4.82 million tablets
of stimulant drugs.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the authorities punished 562 persons including 468
men and 94 women involved in 412 drug-related cases, the report
said.
</P>
<P>
In the 1998-99 opium cultivation season, the Myanmar
authorities destroyed a total of 3,839 hectares of poppy fields
scattered in Shan, Kayah and Kachin states and Mandalay division
in the country.
</P>
<P>
According to official statistics, 10,794 kilos of narcotic
drugs, including 403.8 kilos of heroin and 5,393.6 kilos of opium
as well as 16.02 million stimulant drug tablets were seized in the
country in 1998.
</P>
<P>
During the year, a total of 4,845 drug offenders were punished
in connection with 3,546 related cases. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990527.0269 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bangladesh's GDP Growth Rate Estimated at 5.2 Pct </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, May 27 (Xinhua) -- Bangladesh's growth rate in the gross
domestic product (GDP) during the outgoing July 1998-June 1999
fiscal year has been estimated at 5.2 percent, The Financial
Express daily newspaper reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"The higher growth rate has been possible because of bumper
crop production this year," State Minister for Planning Mohiuddin
Khan Alamgir was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
Timely steps to recover losses caused by the last year's
devastating floods had also contributed to achieve such a high
growth rate, Khan said.
</P>
<P>
The considerable growth could be achieved due to all-out
efforts of the government and excellent flood management,
according to Prime Minister Sheikh Hasina.
</P>
<P>
"People of all strata worked hard to tide over the situation,"
she said, adding that timely supply of seeds, fertilizer and other
supports provided to the farmers resulted in the bumper harvest of
crops.
</P>
<P>
The growth rate was earlier projected at only 3.8 percent
against the original target of six percent, as the floods, the
worst in a century, caused a huge damage worth 2 billion U.S.
dollars on the economy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
