<DOCNO> XIE19990527.0271 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> "Global Democratization," Camouflage of U.S. Hegemony: Signed Article (3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
It is well-known that the state and national sovereignty have
taken shape gradually in the past thousands of years of human
history.
</P>
<P>
Equality of state sovereignty, mutual recognition and respect
of sovereignty and non-interference in internal affairs are the
most important principles in regard to international relations.
All these have formed the basis of international order and the
foundation for the establishment and existence of the United
Nations. All these are important accomplishments scored by mankind
in contemporary civilization.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. Charter, which was formulated in 1945, explicitly
states that all states enjoy equal sovereignty.
</P>
<P>
The Declaration on Principles of International Law Concerning
Friendly Relations and Cooperation Among States In Accordance with
the Charter of the United Nations, which was ratified in 1970,
reiterates the principle of "equality of sovereignty for all
states."
</P>
<P>
The Charter of Economic Rights and Duties of States, a document
passed in 1974, restates the basic principles of "state
sovereignty, territorial integrity and political independence,"
and "equality of sovereignty for all states." Besides, it also
defines the "economic sovereignty" for states.
</P>
<P>
With regard to the human rights issue, the UN. General Assembly
adopted the Declaration of Non-interference and Nonintervention in
Others' Internal Affairs in 1981. The Declaration states that all
countries are obliged to avoid making use of and distorting human
right issues as a means of imposing pressure upon other countries
or creating suspicion and confusion in other countries or inside a
group of countries or among one another.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990527.0272 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> "Global Democratization," Camouflage of U.S. Hegemony: Signed Article (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
In addition, the theory says that with the globalization of the
world economy, the concept for national sovereignty will gradually
be replaced by "global common values" and "the sense of world as a
whole." The notion of national sovereignty has become increasingly
"a reactionary factor" that will fundamentally lead to subjugation,
oppression and war.
</P>
<P>
According to this logic, a "global citizen society" should be
established through "global democratization" to take the place of
the current international relations mechanism based on national
sovereignty.
</P>
<P>
The U.S.-led NATO, ignoring the United Nations, launched air
strikes against Yugoslavia under the pretext of "preventing
humanitarian disasters." In the meantime, they have declared that
with the advent of a new century, the international community
should alter the traditional notion of national sovereignty and
the norms of international relations, and must put restrictions on
the important aspects of the principle of non-interference in
internal affairs.
</P>
<P>
They also declare that "national sovereignty is not so
important as human rights," and that "we have an obligation to
protect human rights worldwide."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
