<HEADLINE> Defense Ministers of Germany, France, Poland Discuss Kosovo Issue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BERLIN, May 26 (Xinhua) -- German Defense Minister Rudolf
Scharping said Wednesday that NATO should maintain heavy military
pressure on Belgrade while continue to seek a political solution
to the Kosovo crisis.
</P>
<P>
Scharping, who had a day-long meeting with his French
counterpart Alai Richard and Polish counterpart Janusz
Onyszkiewicz in Rheinland-Pfalz state Wednesday, said only through
maintaining military pressure can a permanent solution be achieved.
</P>
<P>
However, he believed NATO should also continue to seek a
political solution and offer humanitarian aid to Kosovo refugees.
The most important objective is to achieve NATO's goals, Scharping
said.
</P>
<P>
French Defense Minister Alai Richard said that NATO's air raids
against Yugoslavia have made progress since one-third of
Yugoslavia's armed forces in Kosovo have been destroyed and the
main roads to Kosovo have been bombed out.
</P>
<P>
The French minister wanted NATO's air strikes to continue until
Yugoslavia accepts NATO's demands.
</P>
<P>
The three defense ministers also discussed security and defense
cooperation in Europe. Their meeting was held within the framework
of the Weimar three-nation meeting.
</P>
<P>
In August 1991, foreign ministers of Germany, France and Poland
issued a statement in Weimar vowing to strengthen their countries'
good neighborly cooperation. The cooperation extended to security
and defense in 1994. 
</P>
</TEXT>
