<HEADLINE> "Global Democratization," Camouflage of U.S. Hegemony: signed Article (5) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
An important mission for the United States to push forward "
global democratization" is to spread its own social system and
values worldwide.
</P>
<P>
The reason the United States labels some countries as "rogue
states" is not because these countries violate the norms of
international relations but because they are not obedient to the
United States, or do not accept U.S.-model and dare say "No" to U.
S. hegemony.
</P>
<P>
The essential reason for the U.S.-led NATO to put Yugoslavia on
the black list of "rogue states" and target it for air strikes,
according to the western media, is that the country is "the last
red fort in Europe." The ultimate mission of the ongoing military
operation, henceforth, is to overthrow the "communist regime led
by Milosevic
</P>
<P>
But unlike the old Cold War, the new Cold War, launched by the
United States under the banner of "safeguarding human rights" and
"global democratization" at a time when it is lording it over the
world, is more hegemonic and smells stronger of gunpowder.
</P>
<P>
The initiators of the new Cold War, no longer satisfied with
the general ideological struggle and infiltration or peaceful
evolution, now brazenly interfere in other countries' internal
affairs, trample on their national sovereignty, and seek to impose
their own standard of human rights and values and decided whether
other countries should be granted a "well-behaved ID card" or be
put on the "black list."
</P>
<P>
The United States seeks to be the world's "human rights judge"
and to try the broad developing and socialist countries on their
human rights. It issues annual human rights reports, judging other
countries' human rights, and lodges suits against those countries,
with which it is dissatisfied, at the U.N. Human Rights
Commission's meetings.
</P>
