<HEADLINE> "Global Democratization," Camouflage of U.S. Hegemony: Signed Article (4) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
It is clear that the U.S.-style "global democratization,"
which flaunts that "human rights outweigh sovereignty," is in open
contempt of and a challenge to the UN Charter and all generally
recognized norms of international relations.
</P>
<P>
It is entirely wrong to think that the United States and its
partners, in advocating the "global democratization," are denying
the state sovereignty of their own, and aim to build up a more
fair, democratic and more humanitarian international order through
democratic consultations.
</P>
<P>
What they deny is the sovereignty of the vast majority of
developing countries, for, in their view, it is the sovereignty of
these "ignorant" and "backward" nations, as the United States and
its partners term them, has held back the development of democracy,
freedom and human rights.
</P>
<P>
The sovereignty of the United States and its allies, on the
contrary, is the guarantee of democracy, liberty and human rights
and is the basis for the establishment of a U.S.-pattern global
society with common global value and concepts, they claimed. And
the latter style sovereignty should not be denied but be fortified,
expanded, and even spread to other countries.
</P>
<P>
The "New Concept" and "New Function" of NATO to shift from
defense to assault, expand its "defensive" sphere from within the
member states to places outside of its circle of authority and to
act as human right police in the world are but a demonstration of
such an ideology.
</P>
</TEXT>
