<HEADLINE> Indonesian Election Supervisory Committee Asked to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, May 27 (Xinhua) -- The Urban Poor Consortium (UPC), an
Indonesian non-governmental organization, has demanded that the
Election Supervisory Committee, Attorney General's Office and
Indonesian Police follow up its findings on money politics.
</P>
<P>
Coordinator of UPC Wardah Hafidz made fresh allegations on
Wednesday that ruling Golkar Party and the People's Sovereignty
Party (PDR) misused state facilities, the social safety net fund
and small-scale credit funds.
</P>
<P>
The PDR is known to have close ties with Minister of
Cooperatives and Small Enterprises Adi Sasono.
</P>
<P>
"Golkar and PDR need to be disqualified as contestants in the
June 7 general election for their involvement in money politics,"
Wardah said.
</P>
<P>
According to Wardah, her group's findings on money politics as
practiced by the two parties were reported by field workers from
various areas.
</P>
<P>
The general pattern being used by the two parties includes the
use of the social safety net program funds and farming credits,
she said.
</P>
<P>
"In most of the cases we discovered, farmers were given loans
by cooperatives, but for the payoff they had to become members of
PDR," Wardah was quoted by The Jakarta Post Thursday as saying.
</P>
<P>
She said there was a case where Golkar officials promised
ginger farmers in Sukabumi, West Java, they would not have to
repay their loans if Golkar won the elections in their area.
However, if Golkar lost, they were told they would have to repay
the loans.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile deputy chairman of the Elections Supervisory
Committee Mulyana W. Kusumah said his office would soon discuss
reports of alleged money politics by PDR and Golkar.
</P>
<P>
The Indonesian Observer quoted some sources as saying that
Golkar officially has at least 11 billion rupiah (1.24 million
U.S. dollars) spread across several bank accounts.
</P>
<P>
In an address to a seminar here on Wednesday, Emil Salim, one
of the country's most respected statesmen, warned that the
credibility of June general election is facing a "real threat"
from money politics.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the University Network for a Free and Fair Election
(Unfrel) Wednesday said most of the violations that occurred
during the enrollment of voters for the general election were
conducted by Golkar Party.
</P>
<P>
They said the violations were found mainly in rural and remote
areas.
</P>
<P>
The organization also reported an alleged violation of election
rules by the Indonesian Democratic Party of Struggle. The party
held an illegal campaign by mobilizing people during the night.
</P>
<P>
Unfrel Coordinator Agung Supriyo said his organization urged
the Election Supervisory Committee to penalize parties that breach
the election law.
</P>
<P>
In a related development, leaders of Golkar's Jakarta chapter
said they would protest if the Jakarta Elections Supervisory
Committee decided to disqualify the chapter from the remainder of
the campaign period for reported campaign violations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
