<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Economic Crime in Czech on Rise </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PRAGUE, May 26 (Xinhua) -- The number of economic crimes in the
Czech Republic in 1998 hit 36,000 cases, up 5,875 cases or 19.5
percent over 1997, said a report published by the Czech Ministry
of the Interior on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Statistics from a report titled: "Czech National Secure Status
in 1998," showed that financial losses resulting from economic
crimes in 1998 amounted to 21 billion koruna (600 million US.
dollars ), an increase of 21.6 percent over 1997.
</P>
<P>
The number of economic crimes increased 95.5 percent and the
losses caused by such crime leaped sharply to 398 percent,
compared to figures in 1993, the report added.
</P>
<P>
At a press conference on Tuesday, officials from the ministry
of the interior admitted that economic crime is a serious problem
facing the country, and pledged to adopt more iron-handed anti-
crime measures.
</P>
<P>
Local analysts say the absence of laws and principles, and the
lack of enforcement in the execution of the laws, are a few of the
main reasons causing an increase in economic crimes. 
</P>
</TEXT>
