<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Partial Access of U.S. Split-Runs to Canadian Advertising Allowed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, May 26 (Xinhua) -- Canada and the United States have
reached a tentative agreement to end their eight-month dispute
over Canada's proposed magazine legislation, announced Canadian
Heritage Minister Sheila Copps and International Trade Minister
Sergio Marchi on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The compromise would allow American publishers that produce
Canadian magazines, also known as split-runs, to print up to 18
percent of Canadian advertising per issue, and the levels would be
phased in over three years, with 12 percent in the first year, 15
in the second and 18 in the third, said the officials.
</P>
<P>
The magazines would have to produce a majority of Canadian
content, or face the original system of fines proposed in Bill C-
55, proposed by the heritage minister last October and designed to
keep out split-runs, which cost little to publish and therefore
can afford to charge advertisers much less than Canadian magazines.
</P>
<P>
Canadian officials initially refused to allow split-runs access
to more than 10 percent of Canadian advertising, while their U.S.
counterparts steadfastly demanded 25 percent.
</P>
<P>
The original structure of the bill would have penalized foreign
publishers that printed Canadian advertising geared towards the
Canadian Market.
</P>
<P>
The Bill went before a Senate committee, which heard Tuesday
from Sergio Marchi. "The right agreement is there. The basic bill
certainly remains," said the international trade minister.
</P>
<P>
Copps and Marchi hailed the bill as proof that the United
States has finally recognized the need for a country to protect
its culture.
</P>
<P>
"For the first time in the history of the United States, they
have recognized that cultural protection and promotion is a
legitimate trade objective," Copps said at a news conference.
</P>
<P>
The Canadian Magazine Publishers Association has said that
granting anything more than 10 percent would cause serious damage
to the national magazine industry.
</P>
<P>
The Canadian government will provide up to 100 million Canadian
Dollars (68 million U.S. dollars) in subsidies to help the
Canadian industry adjust, another official source said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
