<HEADLINE> Annan, Russia Foreign Minister Meet on Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
STOCKHOLM, May 26 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan
and Russian Foreign Minister Igor Ivanov met here Wednesday to
discuss the Kosovo crisis, with neither side releasing any new
information that might be considered special after their talks.
</P>
<P>
Annan said at a news briefing that they focused on "What the
next step will be once we have a breakthrough."
</P>
<P>
He said the United Nations will be able to play a pivotal role
once an agreement on the peaceful solution to the Kosovo crisis is
reached.
</P>
<P>
Ivanov reiterated Russia's stand on the issue, claiming that
NATO has violated international law in its air raids against
Yugoslavia and must end the attacks.
</P>
<P>
Neither Annan nor Ivanov elaborated on the details of their
talks.
</P>
<P>
Annan said he valued the efforts made by Russia's Balkans envoy
Viktor Chernomyrdin, the U.S. Deputy State of Secretary Strobe
Talbott, and Finnish President and European Union envoy Martti
Ahtisaari, to seek a political settlement of the Kosovo crisis.
</P>
<P>
He said all aspects of the international community were making
special efforts for a peaceful solution to the Balkan crisis.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. chief affirmed that prior to his talks with Ivanov, he
made a phone call to Chernomyrdin, Talbott and Ahtisaari, who were
discussing the Kosovo crisis in Moscow. He also talked with his
two Balkan envoys, former Swedish Prime Minister Carl Beldt and
Slovakian Foreign Minister Eduard Kukan, in the Swedish capital.
</P>
<P>
Ivanov met Swedish Prime Minister Goran Persson and Foreign
Minister Anna Lindh before the talks with Annan.
</P>
<P>
The Swedish leaders reportedly stressed Russia's role in
settling the Kosovo crisis. Both sides also discussed the
possibility of having Sweden participate in the international
peace-keeping forces to be deployed in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
The Swedish foreign minister said after the talks that Sweden's
involvement in the peace-keeping mission will have U.N. approval.
</P>
<P>
Ivanov arrived here on Wednesday for talks with Swedish leaders.
Annan returned to Moscow on the same day. 
</P>
</TEXT>
