<HEADLINE> Last Gasp Goals Send United to European Glory </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MADRID, May 26 (Xinhua) -- Manchester United produced one of
the most amazing comeback in soccer history to beat Bayern Munich
2-1 with two injury time goals in Wednesday's European Cup final
in Barcelona.
</P>
<P>
German champions Bayern Munich had been leading from the sixth
minute through a Mario Basler free-kick before substitute Teddy
Sheringham equalised with a right-foot shot for Manchester United
in the 89th minute.
</P>
<P>
Ninety seconds later, another substitute Ole Gunnar Solskjaer
of Norway swept in the winner from close range after a David
Beckham corner had been headed on by Sheringham.
</P>
<P>
The victory gave United, who completed an English cup and
league double four days ago, a unique treble in the British soccer
history. And in Europea, United is the only third side to complete
the soccer feat besides Celtic (1967) and Ajax Amsterdam (1972).
</P>
<P>
With captain Roy Keane and midfielder Paul Scholes suspended,
coach Alex Ferguson had to employ David Beckham, Ryan Giggs and
Jesper Blomqvist in unfamiliar positions in midfield.
</P>
<P>
Not until Ferguson abandoned his policy and brought on
Sheringham and Solskjaer in place of Blomqvist and Andy Cole, did
United finally find their way.
</P>
<P>
Bayern had had two golden chances to seal the win when their
substitute Mehmet Scholl hit the post after 78 minutes and Carsten
Jancker hit the bar with an overhead scissor kick six minutes
later.
</P>
<P>
But United, who formed a habit of scoring late goals this
season, refused to give in, and recorded the most dramatic end to
a European final since the event was introduced in 1956.
</P>
<P>
It was United's first European Cup success since their only
previous win in 1968. It was also United's 33rd match without
defeat and secured England's first European Cup success since
Liverpool in 1984.
</P>
<P>
Ferguson, having completed his lifelong ambition which he
stated when he arrived at Old Trafford 13 years ago, now stands as
one of the most successful British managers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
