<HEADLINE> Northeastern Enterprises Attract Talents with High Pays </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGCHUN, May 27 (Xinhua) -- People with special talents or
skills are becoming increasingly expensive in the northeastern
Chinese province of Jilin, where companies are trying to beat the
competition with more attractive salaries.
</P>
<P>
The annual pay being offered to a promising manager at a job
fair in the capital of Jilin on Tuesday, for example, could run as
high as 160,000 yuan. There were 51 enterprises at the fair
competing for people to fill 10 job spots by bidding.
</P>
<P>
The bidding ran from 30,000 yuan to 120,000 yuan for MBAs,
experienced managers, and students who have studied overseas. Han
Guangming, a 34-year-old with a master's degree in marketing, said
that the hot bidding indicated that their knowledge was valuable.
</P>
<P>
One biological products manufacturer hired four people. Its
president Wang Hengwei said that competition in a market economy
is a competition for talented people and that enterprises should
not begrudge paying them well given the high profits they can
produce. 
</P>
</TEXT>
