<HEADLINE> Defending Champion Norway Limps toward Women's World Cup </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, May 26 (Xinhua) -- Norway, the defending women's
World Cup champion, has serious injuries as the team heads to the
World Cup in the United States, according to a press report here
today.
</P>
<P>
USA Today newspaper reported that star defender Gro Espeseth
tore a knee ligament this spring and might have to retire.
Goalkeeper Bente Nordby is out with a knee injury, and forward Ann
Kristin Aarones has a virus.
</P>
<P>
Nordby and Aarones should make the Cup, though they won't be in
top form. Nordby, 24, was the best shooter in the World Cup
champion team in 1995, and helped the team win the bronze medal in
the 1996 Olympic Games. Aarones has played more than 80 games for
Norway since 1990.
</P>
<P>
Norway will announce its 20-player roster on May 31. They will
arrive in the United States in early June to practice and train.
Its first game is on June 24 against Russia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
