<HEADLINE> Greece Supports Bulgaria, Romania's Admission into EU, NATO </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SOFIA, May 26 (Xinhua) -- Bulgaria and Romania's admission into
the European Union (EU) and NATO will not only help strengthen
stability in the Balkan region but also facilitate further
economic development of countries in the region, visiting Greek
President Costis Stephanopoulos said here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Stephanopoulos, who was here on a three-day official visit,
made the remark at a joint news conference with his Bulgarian
counterpart, Peter Stoyanov.
</P>
<P>
During the news conference, the president confirmed Greece's
support for Bulgaria and Romania's efforts to obtain membership in
the two blocs. He described as justified the two countries' wish
for an early launching of admission negotiations.
</P>
<P>
Noting that stability in the Balkans depends on cooperation
among countries in the region, the Greek head of state said
friendship between Bulgaria and Romania is an example of such
cooperation. He pointed out that both countries are interested in
a settlement of the Kosovo conflict as soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
Stoyanov agreed and said, "Today the problem is not only to
establish peace in the Balkans, but also to guarantee stability
and prosperity of the region."
</P>
<P>
He described as making the Balkans an integral part of Europe a
major task after the achievement of peace on the peninsula.
</P>
<P>
Bulgaria is among the countries most interested in achieving
peace in Kosovo, not only because of the humanitarian aspects of
the Kosovo crisis, but also because of the economic losses
Bulgaria has suffered every day since the eruption of the crisis,
Stoyanov said.
</P>
<P>
When asked whether Bulgaria would support the Greek proposal
for a halt to NATO's air strikes against Yugoslavia, he said
Bulgaria will unhesitatingly support every peace proposal
endorsing lasting prospects of stability and prosperity in the
region.
</P>
<P>
Greece supports the need for economic assistance to the Balkan
countries affected by the Kosovo crisis, Stephanopoulos said. The
future reconstruction and economic development of the region are
also major topics between the two presidents.
</P>
<P>
During his stay here, Stephanopoulos will meet Bulgarian Prime
Minister Ivan Kostov, Sofia Mayor Stefan Sofiyanski, and Patriarch
Maksim. He will also attend a Bulgarian-Greek economic forum and
will meet leaders of other political parties.
</P>
<P>
Accompanying the president are Greek Development Minister
Evangelos Venizelos, Deputy Foreign Minister Grigoros Niotis, and
a 25-member business delegation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
