<DOCNO> XIE19990527.0304 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Colombia to Promote Peace Process: President </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CARTAGENA DE INDIAS (Colombia), May 26 (Xinhua) -- Colombian
President Abdres Pastrana said here Wednesday that his government
will further promote the peace process dubbed "Colombians for
Colombians."
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the opening of the 11th summit of the Andean
countries, Pastrana said the government should not fear
negotiating during the process.
</P>
<P>
He said the process has gained support from all sectors, and as
always, from the military forces.
</P>
<P>
Pastrana said the process requires strength to maintain
optimism without losing sight of the objectives, which are to find
the strength to understand, the necessity to adjust to the time
and the terms of the process, and the strength to smooth the way
with imagination and audacity.
</P>
<P>
As president of the summit meeting, the Colombian president
described the help and support from neighboring countries and
friends as another factor of hope and confidence in the peace
process.
</P>
<P>
On the same day, the Colombian military forces repeated its
support to the president after the resignation of Defense Minister
Rodrigo Lloreda.
</P>
<P>
The acting Defense Minister and Commander in Chief of the
Colombian Military Forces General Fernando Tapias, said the
military is devoted to the constitution and to the president of
the republic. He said they were not foes but supporters of the
peace process.
</P>
<P>
General Tapias was appointed as acting defense minister
following the resignation of Rodrigo Lloreda and at least six
other generals who were in disagreement with the ongoing peace
process in the country.
</P>
<P>
On Tuesday, Lloreda stepped up his criticism of government
concessions to the rebel group, which is called the Revolutionary
armed Forces of Colombia (FARC), saying that the government had
given up too much in exchange for little or nothing from FARC.
</P>
<P>
In order to continue the peace process, President Pastrana
ordered all government troops out of an area of 42,000 square
kilometers in November, ceding it to FARC in order to bolster
peace talks and end a conflict that has claimed more than 35,000
lives over the last decade. 
</P>
</TEXT>
