<HEADLINE> Vietnam Grants Most Favored Nation Status to Japan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, May 27 (Xinhua) -- Vietnam granted Most Favored Nation
(MFN) status to Japan on Wednesday, allowing Japanese imports to
enjoy long-term preferential tariffs, press reports said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Vietnam's extension of MFN status to Japan was made on a
reciprocal basis under which the Japanese government Wednesday
granted the same status to Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
The decisions of the two countries were made following an
agreement on the exchange of MFN treatment reached between
Vietnamese Prime Minister Phan Van Khai and his Japanese
counterpart Keizo Obuchi during Khai's visit to Japan in late
March.
</P>
<P>
Two-way trade between Vietnam and Japan reached 3.48 billion
U.S. dollars in 1997. Of this, Vietnamese exports totaled 2.2
billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
Japan is Vietnam's largest bilateral aid donor.
</P>
<P>
Up to now, Vietnam has granted MFN status to 66 countries and
regions including China, Russia, Australia, Canada, Germany and
other ASEAN countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
