<DOCNO> XIE19990527.0307 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More China's Private Businesses Value Talents More Than Family Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHIJIAZHUANG, May 27 (Xinhua) --More private businesses in
China are paying high salaries to talents who are not family
members and are giving them jobs as general managers or putting
them in charge of production and marketing.
</P>
<P>
These people are playing an important role in leading China's
private economy. According to research of the Hebei Provincial
Government's Policy Research Office, among 5,000 private
businesses with assets of more than 10 million yuan, 85 percent
have done away with a family-based, nepotistic management mode and
have started using a professional corporate management system that
emphasizes competence.
</P>
<P>
The Hualian Cashmere Processing Group in Hebei's Qinghe County
is a family business used to be run by eight brothers each of whom
has only nine years of schooling, and that made growth difficult,
says Chen Donghua, one of the brothers. So, in the end, they
decided to hire a more capable person from a state-owned
enterprise in Inner Mongolia as a marketing manager.
</P>
<P>
The move has worked. The new manager bases the product mix on
market studies and has made more efforts in opening up markets.
The group is able to earn 12 million yuan from sales in a short
period of time.
</P>
<P>
The improved training of workers has led to increased quality
of products and eventually to improved marketing. To survive in
the fast-growing market, many private businesses that were mom and
pop workshops have stopped relying heavily on processing and begun
to hire more competent people to pursue development that is based
on technology. The State Council's Development and Research Center
says that high-tech companies now account for 12 percent of the
country's private businesses. These companies have developed more
than 10,000 new products, many of which are in line with
international standards. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
