<DOCNO> XIE19990527.0311 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> "Global Democratization," Camouflage of U.S. Hegemony: Article (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 27 (Xinhua) -- Xinhua today published a signed
article by Wang Jincun, a senior researcher with the Chinese
Academy of Social Sciences. The full text of the article, entitled
"Global Democratization -- Camouflage of U.S. Hegemony," reads as
following:
</P>
<P>
While striving to build a single-polared world and to
strengthen its hegemony, the United States has put forward various
kinds of power politics theories. One example of these is the "
global democratization" concept.
</P>
<P>
After launching the war of aggression against Yugoslavia, the U.
S.-led NATO has trumpeted the theory in a bigger way, in an
attempt to cover up its atrocities. What on earth is the "global
democratization?"
</P>
<P>
The critical points of "global democratization" are to deprive
and to trample on the sovereignty of developing nations. The
theoretical basis for "global democratization" is the so-called "
modern sovereignty theory" or the "limited sovereignty theory", or
the "democracy leading to peace theory", or the theory that
national sovereignty is an outdated notion. These theories have
been popular for some time in the United States and some other
NATO member nations.
</P>
<P>
The core of the "global democratization" concept is the so-
called "global democracy value" and the theory that "human rights
outweigh national sovereignty." According to the theory, the
concept of national sovereignty and the principles of
international relations based on national sovereignty are outmoded.
Even the United Nations and the UN Charter, established according
to the principle of national sovereignty, are also out of fashion.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990527.0312 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Argentina Denies Peso's Devaluation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUENAS AIRES, May 26 (Xinhua) -- Argentina's Vice Minister of
Economy Pablo Guidotti said on Wednesday that the rumours of a
possible devaluation of the Argentine currency, the peso, "have no
foundation."
</P>
<P>
These rumours have affected the local markets of the country
and the region, and have arisen "for speculative reasons," over
the past few days, he said.
</P>
<P>
"Fortunately, the markets have calmed down in the face of the
evidence that there will not be changes" he said, referring to the
Argentine policy on the free exchange of the peso against the U.S.
dollar, which was initiated on April 1, 1991.
</P>
<P>
"These types of rumours cannot last more than two or three days,
as they were absolutely groundless," said Guidotti at a press
conference.
</P>
<P>
The exchange rate of the Argentine peso against the U.S. dollar
stood at 1:1.0005 Wednesday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
