<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0100 GMT, May 27 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- The U.S. Senate Wednesday rejected the Bill
Clinton administration's request to close more military bases as a
cost-saving measure.
</P>
<P>
The 60-to-40 Senate vote rejected a move by Republican Senator
John McCain and Democratic Senator Carl Levin to authorize a new
round of base closings in 2001.
</P>
<P>
This was the third year in a row Congress has blocked the plan.
(US-Senate-Bill)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS -- The U.N. Security Council Wednesday voiced "
deep concern" at the humanitarian situation in Angola, saying that
it is the responsibility of the Angolan Government and the rebel
National Union for Total Independence of Angola (UNITA) to
cooperate with the United Nations in rendering humanitarian
assistance to all the people in need. (UN-Angola-Statement)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- Greek Foreign Minister George Papandreou
Wednesday called for a pause in NATO bombing of Yugoslavia to
encourage Yugoslavia to respond positively to tough demands for
settlement of the Kosovo conflict.
</P>
<P>
After a meeting with U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright,
Papandreou reaffirmed the Greek proposal that there should be a
pause in NATO's bombing to give some stimulus to the diplomatic
efforts. (US-Greece-Kosovo)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- A Senior Chinese Diplomat refuted here Wednesday
the U.S. allegation that China has "stolen" nuclear secrets from
the United States.
</P>
<P>
"As Chinese leaders and spokesman of the Chinese government
have repeatedly said, China has never stolen any nuclear secrets
from the United States," said Liu Xiaoming, Minister of the
Chinese Embassy in the United States, in a CNN interview. (US-
China Diplomat)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BONN -- Key German leaders Wednesday said NATO's five demands
to Yugoslavia as condition for halting air attacks were not
negotiable.
</P>
<P>
The five demands include the withdrawal of all Yugoslav troops
from Kosovo and deployment of an international force with NATO
troops at its core.
</P>
<P>
NATO's demands "must be met without any limitations," said
Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder after talks with visiting Bulgarian
Prime Minister Ivan Kostov in Bonn.
</P>
<P>
But the details and the timetable may be part of negotiations,
he added. (Germany-NATO-Yugoslavia)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
PARIS -- France said on Wednesday that it is ready to raise the
level of participation in the future "force of peace in Kosovo (
KFOR)," after NATO decided to raise the number of soldiers in the
KFOR from 28,000 to 45,000.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman of the French Defense Ministry Jean-Francois
Bureau said that the volume of participation by each country to
participate in the KFOR will be decided next week by NATO. (France-
Kosovo)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
MOSCOW -- Russia announced Wednesday that it has developed a
new anti-ship missile that will "revolutionize the nature of a
naval battle," the Itar-Tass news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The new missile, ZM-54E1, developed by the Novator Experimental
Design Bureau in Yekaterinburg, is 6.2 meters long, the same as
the length of the standard torpedo tubes used by Western navies,
Tass said, quoting Deputy General Designer Vyacheslav Gorbarenko.
(Russia-Navy Missile)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
TIRANA -- A new wave of Kosovo refugees has occurred at the
border crossings between Yugoslavia and Macedonia over the past
few days.
</P>
<P>
According to the Macedonian news agency MIA, 13,222 from Kosovo
entered Macedonia in the 24 hours from 7 a.m. Monday to 7 a.m.
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Among the new comers, 11,742 crossed into Macedonia through the
Blace border point, 1,214 through Jaznice and 266 through
Tabanovce. (Macedonia-Refugees-Influx) 
