<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Carter Named NBA Rookie of the Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, May 26 (Xinhua) -- Vince Carter, who led the
Toronto Raptors in scoring while becoming known for his thunderous
and spectacular dunks, today was named as the runaway winner of
the NBA's Rookie of the Year award.
</P>
<P>
Carter received all but five of a possible 118 votes from a
panel of sports writers and broadcasters. Sacramento Kings point
guard Jason Williams finished second and forward Paul Pierce of
the Boston Celtics was third.
</P>
<P>
Cater was selected fifth overall last June by the Golden State
Warriors but was traded on draft day to Toronto for the previous
pick, Antawn Jamision, who teamed with Carter in leading North
Carolina to back-to-back Final Fours in 1997 and 1998.
</P>
<P>
Toronto went a respectable 23-27, missing an Eastern Conference
playoff spot by four games with Carter as the go-to-player from
the outset. He led all rookies with 18.3 points per game and
scored 20 or more points 20 times.
</P>
<P>
Carter, who scored a season-high 32 points in a loss at Houston
on March 24, also averaged 5.7 rebounds, 3.0 assists, 1.54 blocked
shots and 1.10 steals while shooting 45 percent from the field
over 35.2 minutes per game. He started 40 of Toronto's 50 games.
</P>
<P>
Named Rookie of the Month for March and April, Carter was the
only rookie this season to garner Player of the Week honors, doing
so after leading the Raptors to a 5-0 record during the week
ending March 21. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990527.0318 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-27 </DATE_TIME>
