<DOCNO> XIE19990527.0319 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Statistics Show Duncan More Impressive Than Malone </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, May 26 (Xinhua) -- All indications are that Karl
Malone is about to be announced as the winner of this season's NBA
Most Valuable Player Award, but all statistics have showed Tim
Duncan is better than him in many fields.
</P>
<P>
Based on a rating system that compares 10 of objective
statistical categories, though, Malone gets edged out for MVP by
San Antonio's Duncan and Shaquille O'Neal of the Los Angeles
Lakers comes in third.
</P>
<P>
The 10 candidates were picked subjectively by sportswriters and
sportscasters who regularly cover the league and the criteria are
subjective.
</P>
<P>
The candidates ranked against each other in 10 categories
designed to evaluate a player's total value. The candidates
selected, along with Duncan, Malone and O'neal were Alonzo
Mourning, Grant Hill, Allen Iverson, Gary Payton, Jason Kidd,
Kevin Garnett and Chris Webber.
</P>
<P>
The categories are field goal percentage, free throws made a
game, scoring average, rebound average, assist average, points
scored per shot attempt, away attendance, winning percentage of
the player's team, the number of games missed and hands, which
adds steals and blocked shots and subtracts turnovers and personal
fouls.
</P>
<P>
The player with the best performance in a particular category
was given one point and the worst in a category was given 10
points. The points in all 10 categories were added, the lowest
total score is the MVP.
</P>
<P>
Malone was the only player to finish first in at least three
categories. Duncan had two firsts and was in the top five in seven
of the 10 categories.
</P>
<P>
Fourth place Mourning was in the top three in six categories
but was last in assists and next to last in games played. Allen
Iverson, buoyed by a first in scoring, and seconds in attracting
fans and in free throws made per game, finished sixth. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990527.0320 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mexico Refuses to Send Troops to Balkans </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, May 26 (Xinhua) -- The Mexican government
Wednesday refused to send troops to the Balkans in a peace
operation supported by the United Nations (UN).
</P>
<P>
"Mexico has never, and will never, have troop participation in
any peacekeeping operation of the UN," said a statement issued by
the Mexican Foreign Ministry.
</P>
<P>
The statement also said that the Mexican government has
expressed "on various occasions" that its foreign policy is
attached "strictly to the constitutional principles of peaceful
solutions to disputes and those of non-intervention."
</P>
<P>
The Yugoslav ambassador in Mexico, Dusan Vasic, was summoned to
the Foreign Ministry on Wednesday to hear Mexico's "strict
attachment to the constitutional principles." 
</P>
