<HEADLINE> Beijing Approves Ten More IT Joint Ventures </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 27 (Xinhua) -- Beijing has recently approved
another ten foreign-funded IT enterprises, making the total number
50 with combined investment of 1.7 billion U.S. dollars, according
to Lin Wenyi, vice-mayor of Beijing.
</P>
<P>
The ten enterprises include Daiichi Pharmaceutical (Beijing) Co.
Ltd., Microsoft (China) Co. Ltd., GE Hangwei Medical Systems Co.,
Ltd., Alcatel (Beijing) Transmission System Co., Ltd. and
Schneider (Beijing) Low Voltage Co., Ltd.
</P>
<P>
Along with the previous 40, they will enjoy all the
preferential policies in accordance with Beijing's regulations for
encouraging foreign investment in high-tech industry.
</P>
<P>
The enterprises are engaged in either information, electronics,
biology, or pharmaceuticals. And the investors consist of
multinational enterprises such as Motorola, Microsoft, Lucent of
the USA, Matsushita, Hitachi, and Mitsubishi of Japan, Bayer, and
Siemens of German and Ericsson of Sweden.
</P>
<P>
All the approved enterprises will be entitled to conditional
tax reductions or even exemptions and prior consideration during
the examination and approval, registration, bank loans, customs
procedures, the setting up of overseas branches, and utility of
public facilities.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that there are over 5,000 high-tech enterprises
in Beijing now, which will contribute to the development of the
local economy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
