<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hingis Overcomes Local Favorite, Kafelnikov out </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, May 26 (Xinhua) -- World top man Yevgeny Kafelnikov of
Russia was eliminated at the French Open on Wednesday while his
woman counterpart Swiss Martina Hingis repeated her Australian
Open final victory over the local favorite Amelie Mauresmo.
</P>
<P>
Hingis's comprehensive 6-3, 6-3 second round victory made her
another step towards the only Grand Slam title to elude her in her
young career.
</P>
<P>
Men's event saw the biggest upsets so far thrown up as top seed
Kafelnikov and fifth seed Dutchman Richard Krajicek both made
early exits.
</P>
<P>
Kafelnikov was swept out of the tournament 6-4, 6-1, 6-4 by
Slovakia's Dominik Hrbaty while Krajicek was humiliated by young
American Vince Spadea 6-1, 6-2, 6-4.
</P>
<P>
Andre Agassi, the 13th seed, narrowly escaped another seeded
scalp, surviving a tense five-set battle with Frenchman Arnaud
Clement 6-2, 4-6, 2-6, 7-5, 6-0.
</P>
<P>
Defending champion and fourth seed Spaniard Carlos Moya also
received an early scare, dropping the opening set to Australian
Open champion Petr Korda of the Czech Republic before recovering
to record a comfortable 6-7, 6-4, 6-3, 6-1 victory.
</P>
<P>
Ninth seeded Chilean Marcelo Rios breezed into the third round
with a straight sets win over Frenchman Arnaud Boetsch while
seventh seed Tim Henman of Britain went past the Czech Republic's
Jiri Novak.
</P>
<P>
In the day's other women's competitions, the Williams sisters,
fifth seed Venus and 10th seed Serena, powered into the third
round with 7-6, 6-0 victory over Natasha Zvereva of Belarus and 6-
3, 6-4 win over Argentina's Mariana Diaz Oliva respectively.
</P>
<P>
Seventh seed and defending champion Spaniard Aranxta Sanchez
Vicario demolished Katarina Srebotnik of Slovenia 6-1, 6-2.
</P>
</TEXT>
