<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Auctions Old Grain Reserves </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 27 (Xinhua) -- China yesterday auctioned some of
its old grain reserves in Zhengzhou, capital of central China's
Henan province.
</P>
<P>
The batch of grain was mostly imported from Canada, the United
States and Australia in 1996, according to today's China Daily.
</P>
<P>
The auction was organized by the State Grain Reserves Bureau,
the Agricultural Development Bank, the Ministry of Finance and the
State Development Planning Commission. The Zhengzhou Commodities
Exchange was the broker of the sales.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, China imported 8.25 million tons of wheat, although
its wheat yields that year amounted to 110.57 million tons,
according to the National Bureau of Statistics.
</P>
<P>
The auction will give the State experience to further break the
monopoly of the country's grain distribution system, which for
decades has been operated by State-run grain supply and marketing
companies, a grain expert was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
In the past, the government used to reduce grain surplus by
allocating it to lower administrative levels.
</P>
<P>
The expert reasoned that the development also reflects the
government's confidence in the wheat yields this year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
