<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bank Savings Still Favored in Shanghai </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, May 27 (Xinhua) -- Most residents in China's leading
industrial and commercial city of Shanghai still prefer putting
their spare money in bank deposit accounts to other ways of saving,
according to a recent sample survey.
</P>
<P>
The survey, conducted by the Shanghai Economic Society,
indicates that about 64 percent of the 8,441 respondents choose to
put their spare money in banks.
</P>
<P>
Only 22.8 percent of the residents surveyed would like to
invest in securities and futures, 9.9 percent prefer to buy
insurance policies, and another 18.5 percent will spend their
spare cash on tourism.
</P>
<P>
Most people say they are saving for a wide range of purposes
such as the education of children and helping out with family
expenses in future years.
</P>
<P>
Geng Zhongping, a professor with Shanghai's Tongji University,
who was in charge of the survey, said that the results show local
residents are more active in preventing risks in life.
</P>
<P>
Chinese people depended on the state for nearly everything in
the past few decades, Geng added.
</P>
<P>
Official estimates put the average total savings value of
Shanghai residents at 21,000 yuan per person by the end of 1997,
in addition to an average of 2,000 yuan worth of stocks and
securities.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990527.0335 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Four Sentenced in Southern City for Kidnapping </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, May 27 (Xinhua) -- A court in the city of Foshan in
south China's Guangdong Province has sentenced four people to life
or fixed terms of imprisonment for kidnapping two people.
</P>
<P>
Liu Xinghua and Ke Yingguang were sentenced to life
imprisonment and deprived of their political rights for life by
the court which sat Tuesday. Liu Guoshun and Liu Yonghua were
sentenced to 14 years and 10 years imprisonment respectively and
given fines of 14,000 yuan and 10,000 yuan each.
</P>
<P>
The four were charged with kidnapping the son of a Hong Kong
businessman in 1992 and a Hong Kong businessman in 1993 and
demanding ransoms totaling five million Hong Kong dollars.
</P>
<P>
They are believed to be members of a criminal gang led by Hong
Kong resident Cheung Tze-keung, who was sentenced to death by the
Intermediate People's Court of Guangzhou, capital of Guangdong
Province, last December.
</P>
<P>
The 36-member gang, 18 from Hong Kong and the rest from
mainland, committed a series of felonies in Hong Kong and the
mainland where they were all arrested.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
