<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IMF Approves 300-Million-Dollar Credit for Algeria </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, May 26 (Xinhua) -- The International Monetary Fund
(IMF) approved on Wednesday a credit totaling 300 million U.S.
dollars for Algeria under the Compensatory and Contingency
Financing Facility (CCFF) to help the African country offset a
temporary shortfall in exports of goods and services.
</P>
<P>
The CCFF aims to assist IMF members experiencing temporary
shortfalls in export earnings. The loans are repayable between
3.25 and 5 years, and carry a standard annual interest charge,
which is currently 3.52 percent.
</P>
<P>
The Algerian economy remains heavily dependent on the petroleum
sector, which accounts for about one quarter of gross domestic
product (GDP), and contributes slightly more than half of
government revenues, and virtually all of the country's export
receipts.
</P>
<P>
In 1998, the external environment worsened as the average oil
export price fell by 33 percent. Consequently, the fiscal balance
moved from a surplus of 2.4 percent of GDP in 1997 to a deficit in
1998 of 3.9 percent of GDP and the external current account
deteriorated sharply from a surplus of 7 percent of GDP to a
deficit of about 2 percent of GDP.
</P>
<P>
Nevertheless, thanks to a recovery in agricultural output and a
turnaround in industrial activity, estimated real GDP grew by 4
percent in 1998.
</P>
<P>
"Despite a modest recovery in world oil and gas prices,
Algeria's external position has continued to be adversely
affected," the IMF said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
"Against this background, the Algerian authorities remain
committed to build on the stabilization achievements of the last
three years, and it is expected that the direction of economic
policy-making will be maintained by the new government toward
ensuring macroeconomic stability and accelerating structural
reforms," it added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990527.0348 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Romania Scores Record Suicides in 1998 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, May 26 (Xinhua) -- Romania scored in the year 1998
the biggest number of suicides in the last decade, the official
Rompres news agency Wednesday reported quoting data supplied by
National Forensic Medicine Institute.
</P>
<P>
As many as 3,660 suicide cases were registered all over Romania
in the year 1998, which means a surge of 6.4 percent against 1997
and of 24.8 percent against 1996. The annual national average
amounts to 14.6 suicides in 100,000 inhabitants.
</P>
<P>
Forensic experts analysed the suicide rate over 1985-1989
compared with the period after 1990 and found that the fast,
progressive deterioration of Romania's social, economic and
political life was in direct proportion to the number of people
who committed suicide.
</P>
<P>
After 1990 a permanent increase of the figure was noticed, with
the climax year of 1998. The ascending curve was put and end to in
the election year 1996 which, maybe, gave the Romanians hope, so
that only 267 suicides were scored, but it was resumed later.
</P>
<P>
The average age of those who committed suicide is 50.9, showed
the data of National Forensic Medicine Institute. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
