<DOCNO> XIE19990527.0349 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Schroeder, Fischer Say NATO's Five Demands Not Negotiable </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, May 26 (Xinhua)--Key German leaders Wednesday said NATO's
five demands to Yugoslavia as condition for halting air attacks
were not negotiable.
</P>
<P>
The five demands include withdrawal of all Yugoslav troops from
Kosovo and deployment of an international force with NATO troops
at its core.
</P>
<P>
NATO's demands "must be met without any limitations," said
Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder after talks with visiting Bulgarian
Prime Minister Ivan Kostov in Bonn.
</P>
<P>
But the details and the timetable may be part of negotiations,
he added.
</P>
<P>
Foreign Minister Joschka Fischer echoed Schroeder's statement
by saying NATO would not be ready for a compromise with
Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
After meeting with visiting British Foreign Secretary Robin
Cook, Fischer said: " militarily we are superior to Yugoslavia,
and we are more determined."
</P>
<P>
But Fischer again ruled out any possibility that Germany send
ground combat forces to Kosovo, saying it a "hypothetical
question".
</P>
<P>
The German parliament has only pass a bill for sending
peacekeeping forces in Kosovo after diplomatic negotiations, he
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
