<DOCNO> XIE19990527.0350 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Stocks Rebound on Wall Street </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, May 26 (Xinhua) -- Wall Street stocks rebounded
strongly Wednesday as traders eased their concerns about higher
interest rates.
</P>
<P>
The Dow Jones industrial average closed up 171.07 at 10,702.16.
The index lost 356.26 points or 3.2 percent in the past four
sessions.
</P>
<P>
Broader stock indicators were also higher. The Standard &AMP;
Poor's 500 index rose 20.36 at 1,304.76 and the technology heavy
Nasdaq composite index rose 46.28 at 2,427.18.
</P>
<P>
Investors' concerns about interest rates were eased after the
Commerce Department reported that orders for big-ticket
manufactured goods fell 2.3 percent last month. The report showed
evidence that the economic is not overheated so that the Federal
Reserve has no need to raise interest rates.
</P>
<P>
In response to a 0.7 percent increase in consumer prices in
April, the Federal Reserve decided a week ago to leave interest
rates unchanged but leaned to monetary tightening if more signs of
inflationary pressures emerge. The move had pulled the market
down.
</P>
<P>
The NYSE composite index rose 7.50 at 624.84 and the American
Stock Exchange index rose 3.82 at 782.66. The Russell 2000 index
of smaller companies rose 0.96 at 435.41.
</P>
<P>
Declining issues barely outnumbered advancers on the New York
Stock Exchange, with 1,498 down, 1,477 up and 557 unchanged.
</P>
<P>
NYSE volume increased to 868.39 million shares from 816.28
million in the previous session. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
